{"title_page": "Steve Bullock (American politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Steve Bullock}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|24th Governor of Montana}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Steve Bullock\n| image = Steve Bullock by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| order = 24th [[List of governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]]\n| lieutenant = [[John Walsh (U.S. senator)|John Walsh]]<br>[[Angela McLean]]<br>[[Mike Cooney]]\n| term_start = January 7, 2013\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Brian Schweitzer]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = Chair of the [[National Governors Association]]\n| term_start1 = July 21, 2018\n| term_end1 = July 26, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Brian Sandoval]]\n| successor1 = [[Larry Hogan]]\n| office2 = 23rd [[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]]\n| governor2 = Brian Schweitzer\n| term_start2 = January 5, 2009\n| term_end2 = January 7, 2013\n| predecessor2 = [[Mike McGrath]]\n| successor2 = [[Tim Fox (politician)|Tim Fox]]\n| birth_name = Stephen Clark Bullock\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Missoula, Montana]], U.S.\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lisa Downs|1999}}\n| children = 3<ref>{{cite web |url=https://biographytree.com/biography/lisa-bullock-biography-wife-governor-steve-bullock |title=Lisa Bullock Biography - Wife of Governor Steve Bullock |date=March 28, 2017 |website=Biographytree.com |accessdate=July 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013111/https://biographytree.com/biography/lisa-bullock-biography-wife-governor-steve-bullock/|archive-date=July 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| residence = [[Montana Governor's Residence|Governor's Residence]]\n| education = [[Claremont McKenna College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Columbia University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| signature = Bullock sig.png\n}}\n'''Stephen Clark Bullock''' (born April 11, 1966) is an American politician, lawyer, and former professor serving as the [[List of Governors of Montana|24th]] and current [[List of Governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\nBorn in [[Missoula, Montana]], Bullock graduated from [[Claremont McKenna College]] and [[Columbia Law School]].  He began his career working as legal counsel to the [[Secretary of State of Montana]] before becoming the Executive Assistant Attorney General and acting Chief Deputy Attorney General of Montana. Bullock then entered private practice as an lawyer for [[Steptoe & Johnson]]. He was an adjunct professor at the [[George Washington University Law School]] before opening his own law firm upon returning to Montana. In 2008, Bullock was elected [[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]], and he served one term from 2009 to 2013.\n\nBullock declared his candidacy for Governor of Montana on September 7, 2011. The seat was open in 2012, as incumbent Governor [[Brian Schweitzer]], a Democrat, could not seek reelection due to term limits. Bullock won the Democratic primary with 87% of the vote and defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Rick Hill]] in the [[2012 Montana gubernatorial election|general election]] with 48% of the vote. In [[2016 Montana gubernatorial election|2016]], Bullock won re-election with 50.2% of the vote, defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Greg Gianforte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/11/28/elizabeth-warren-and-9-other-democrats-i-left-off-my-2020-presidential-list|title=Why I left Elizabeth Warren off my 2020 presidential list (and why I was wrong)|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603193443/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/11/28/elizabeth-warren-and-9-other-democrats-i-left-off-my-2020-presidential-list/|archive-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/23/opinion/red-state-hope-for-democratic-blues.html|title=Red State Hope for Democratic Blues|first=Timothy|last=Egan|date=December 23, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2017|via=NYTimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819022144/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/23/opinion/red-state-hope-for-democratic-blues.html|archive-date=August 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock chaired the [[National Governors Association]] from 2018 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=State of Montana |title=Governor Steve Bullock |accessdate=July 20, 2018 |url=http://governor.mt.gov/Home/Governor |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225438/http://governor.mt.gov/Home/Governor |archive-date=July 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hanson |first=Amy Beth |publisher=Flathead Beacon |title=Bullock Outlines Jobs Initiative for Governors Association |date=July 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 20, 2018 |url=https://flatheadbeacon.com/2018/07/16/bullock-outlines-jobs-initiative-governors-association/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225350/https://flatheadbeacon.com/2018/07/16/bullock-outlines-jobs-initiative-governors-association/ |archive-date=July 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was a [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic candidate]] for [[President of the United States]] in [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]].<ref>{{cite tweet |title=To give everyone a fair shot, we must do more than defeat Donald Trump. We have to defeat the corrupt system that keeps people like him in power, and we need a fighter who's done it before. That's why I'm running for President. Join our team: http://stevebullock.com |number=1128238526330359808|date=14 May 2019|user=GovernorBullock|author=Steve Bullock}}</ref> After suspending his presidential campaign, he announced his candidacy for the [[United States Senate]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Montana|2020 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/9/21166028/steve-bullock-montana-senate-race-democrats|title=Gov. Steve Bullock just made the Montana Senate race competitive for Democrats|publisher=Vox|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nBullock was born in [[Missoula, Montana]], and raised in [[Helena, Montana|Helena]], the state capital. He is the son of Penny Clark, a school board trustee, and Mike Bullock, a teacher and administrator.<ref>[http://stevebullock.com/bullock-seeks-governors-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect-union-rights \"Bullock vows to create jobs and protect union rights\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20141119000616/http://stevebullock.com/bullock-seeks-governors-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect-union-rights|date=November 19, 2014}}, stevebullock.com; accessed September 17, 2015.</ref> He graduated from [[Helena High School]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801200809/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=August 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was in grade school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-fox-go-toe-to-toe-in-attorney-general-race/article_84f43fff-4029-5e77-af07-c1d2ca51db4b.html|title=Bullock, Fox go toe-to-toe in attorney general race|last=McKee|first=Jennifer|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=September 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034454/https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-fox-go-toe-to-toe-in-attorney-general-race/article_84f43fff-4029-5e77-af07-c1d2ca51db4b.html|archive-date=September 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock received his B.A. degree in Politics, Philosophy, and Economics from [[Claremont McKenna College]] and his J.D. degree with honors from [[Columbia Law School]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock profile|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801200809/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=August 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tsl.news/steve-bullock-montana-governor-president/ |title=Q&A: Montana Gov. Steve Bullock CM \u201988 on college experience, potential presidential run  |access-date=April 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430151555/https://tsl.news/steve-bullock-montana-governor-president/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bullock served as chief legal counsel to [[Secretary of State of Montana|Montana Secretary of State]] [[Mike Cooney]]. He went on to work for four years with the Montana Department of Justice under Attorney General Joe Mazurek, first as executive assistant attorney general, and later as acting chief deputy (1997\u20132001).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730231720/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=July 30, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> During this time, he also served as legislative director, coordinating the Attorney General's legislative efforts. As an Assistant Attorney General, Bullock wrote the landmark opinion that guaranteed public access to streams and rivers.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nHe was unsuccessful in his first race for Montana Attorney General, losing in the 2000 Democratic primary to [[Mike McGrath]], who went on to be elected Attorney General that year and currently serves as Chief Justice of the [[Montana Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 Statewide General Canvass|url=http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2000/2000Prim/2000-PrimState.pdf|publisher=Montana Secretary of State|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228155901/http://sos.mt.gov/Elections/Archives/2000s/2000/2000Prim/2000-PrimState.pdf|archivedate=December 28, 2013}}</ref> From 2001 to 2004, Bullock practiced law in Washington, D.C., with Steptoe & Johnson, where he served as an adjunct professor at George Washington University Law School. He returned to Montana in 2004, working in private practice in Helena where he represented individuals, consumer organizations, labor unions, peace officers, associations of political subdivisions, as well as small and large businesses.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Attorney General==\nBullock was the Democratic nominee for Attorney General in 2008, defeating two other candidates in the primary election in June. He went on to win the contested general election race with 52.64% of the vote against Republican Tim Fox. Bullock received 245,669 votes, more than either other candidate.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=2008 Statewide General Canvass|url=http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2008/results/2008_State_General.pdf|publisher=Montana Secretary of State|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115412/http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2008/results/2008_State_General.pdf|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> He pushed for tougher drunken driving laws and a crackdown on prescription drug abuse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prescription Drug Abuse: What We\u2019re Doing|url=https://doj.mt.gov/prescriptiondrugabuse/what-were-doing/|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731024102/https://doj.mt.gov/prescriptiondrugabuse/what-were-doing/|archive-date=July 31, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He introduced the 24/7 Sobriety Program for repeat DUI offenders statewide.<ref>{{cite web|title=MT Senate Committee passes 24/7 Sobriety Program.|url=http://www.kpax.com/news/mt-senate-committee-passes-24-7-sobriety-program/|publisher=KPAX}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This program requires repeat drunk drivers to take breath tests twice a day. The program is aimed at keeping highways and communities free of drunk drivers, and keeping non-violent offenders out of jail and off the public rolls. The program has had success in dropping DUI offenses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Testing keeps most DUI suspects sober.|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/opinion/editorial/gazette-opinion/gazette-opinion-daily-testing-keeps-most-dui-suspects-sober/article_2dcad937-d778-5192-94fa-2b1699146cd8.html|publisher=The Billings Gazette|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031103627/http://billingsgazette.com/news/opinion/editorial/gazette-opinion/gazette-opinion-daily-testing-keeps-most-dui-suspects-sober/article_2dcad937-d778-5192-94fa-2b1699146cd8.html|archive-date=October 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Attorney General's office also pursued the railroad industry for monopolistic business practices,<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana AG sues Burlington Northern to cover some rail costs|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-ag-sues-burlington-northern-to-cover-some-rail-costs/article_3ac485e8-d389-11de-a252-001cc4c03286.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock: State must protect agricultural producers|url=http://missoulian.com/news/local/bullock-state-must-protect-agriculture-producers/article_8f878094-6cdb-5181-b6b1-106dcab963fb.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119091940/https://missoulian.com/news/local/bullock-state-must-protect-agriculture-producers/article_8f878094-6cdb-5181-b6b1-106dcab963fb.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and led the way in stopping an anti-competitive merger between two the largest meat packers in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana leads 16-state effort to save small farms and ranches|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-leads--state-effort-to-save-small-farms-and/article_132b32fe-3516-11df-b42f-001cc4c03286.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119091913/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-leads--state-effort-to-save-small-farms-and/article_132b32fe-3516-11df-b42f-001cc4c03286.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  Bullock focused on the misclassification of employees as independent contractors and allowing FedEx to avoid paying millions in state taxes and fees. Bullock's efforts resulted in changes by FedEx to comply with federal and state laws.<ref>{{cite web|title=FedEx settles with Montana over classification of delivery drivers|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_077bd806-dcb8-11df-a5d3-001cc4c002e0.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119092029/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_077bd806-dcb8-11df-a5d3-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock attracted national attention by challenging the ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission|Citizens United]]'' decision through his defense of Montana's 100-year-old ban on corporate campaign expenditures.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Montana\u2014Big Sky, Clean Politics|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/15/opinion/la-oe-bullock-citizens-united-montana-supreme-20120615|work=LA Times|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628112854/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/15/opinion/la-oe-bullock-citizens-united-montana-supreme-20120615|archive-date=June 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> After winning in the Montana Supreme Court, the [[United States Supreme Court|U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled against the State of Montana in a 5-4 decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clean and Fair Elections|url=https://doj.mt.gov/campaigns/clean-and-fair-elections/|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730235709/https://doj.mt.gov/campaigns/clean-and-fair-elections/|archive-date=July 30, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Court Declines to Revisit its Citizens United Decision|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/26/us/supreme-court-declines-to-revisit-citizens-united.html|work=New York Times|access-date=February 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204124723/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/26/us/supreme-court-declines-to-revisit-citizens-united.html|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock, who authored the state's opinion guaranteeing access to rivers, streams, and public lands, worked with the legislature and Governor Brian Schweitzer to codify the access opinion into law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridge Access Bill Now Law|url=http://www.plwa.org/viewarticle.php?id=106|publisher=Public Land and Water Access Association, Inc|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628134821/http://www.plwa.org/viewarticle.php?id=106|archive-date=June 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Montana==\n[[File:Steve Bullock 10-31-2012.jpg|thumb|170px|Bullock at a campaign event in [[Glasgow, Montana]], October 31, 2012.]]\n\n===Elections===\n{{Main|2012 Montana gubernatorial election|2016 Montana gubernatorial election}}\nBullock announced on September 7, 2011, that he would be a candidate for the Democratic nomination for Governor of Montana in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock announces Democratic run for governor via internet, Billings event|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_d0d56966-d991-11e0-81a9-001cc4c002e0.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203193734/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_d0d56966-d991-11e0-81a9-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=February 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the Democratic primary, Bullock faced off against Helena resident Heather Margolis. Bullock won with 87% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock, Hill win governor primaries|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-hill-win-governor-primaries/article_f1a9c838-b251-514b-8d64-4561b8d179ae.html|publisher=Billings Gazette|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710035623/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-hill-win-governor-primaries/article_f1a9c838-b251-514b-8d64-4561b8d179ae.html|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock and his running mate, then Adjutant General of Montana [[John Walsh (U.S. politician)|John Walsh]], proposed a jobs plan that focuses on small and medium-sized Montana businesses as the engines of job creation. Bullock and General Walsh support:<ref>{{cite web|title=A Jobs Plan for Montana: Part 1: Creating Opportunities for Small Business|url=http://stevebullock.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/BULLOCK-WALSH-JOBS-PLAN-Creating-Opportunites-for-Small-Business.pdf|publisher=stevebullock.com|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517230239/http://stevebullock.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/BULLOCK-WALSH-JOBS-PLAN-Creating-Opportunites-for-Small-Business.pdf|archive-date=May 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Streamlining the regulatory permitting process and establishing a new permit tracking system,\n* Ensuring that government services meet the demands of job creators,\n* Supporting rapid growth in eastern Montana by ensuring that communities receive funds before or in preparation for natural resource development rather than afterwards,\n* Promoting the hiring of Montanans first for jobs inside the state paid for by taxpayers\u2019 money,\n* Expanding in-state business activity to create a business climate that spurs faster expansion and greater business-to-business activity among Montana companies,\n* Further reforming Montana's workers\u2019 compensation system to reduce the number of workers who are injured or killed on the job, getting injured workers back to work as soon as possible and controlling medical costs.\n* Requiring major firms that are awarded state contracts to subcontract a substantial percentage of their work to in-state businesses.\n\nBullock proposed a $400 property tax rebate for homeowners in Montana to spur job creation and refund a portion of the state's $400 million budget surplus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock Proposes $400 tax rebates for Montana homeowners|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-proposes-tax-rebates-for-montana-homeowners/article_42828330-b3f5-11e1-832a-0019bb2963f4.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630221955/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-proposes-tax-rebates-for-montana-homeowners/article_42828330-b3f5-11e1-832a-0019bb2963f4.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJohn Walsh, Bullock's running mate, is the former Adjutant General of the Montana National Guard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Democrat Bullock taps former Montana adjutant general for lieutenant governor|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_f2655054-6998-11e1-8e46-001871e3ce6c.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819234316/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_f2655054-6998-11e1-8e46-001871e3ce6c.html|archive-date=August 19, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock won the election, held on November 6, 2012, defeating Republican ex-US Representative Rick Hill.<ref>[http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/networks-declare-bullock-winner-in-tight-race-for-governor/article_6e665ae8-252f-11e2-b495-001a4bcf887a.html Networks Declare Bullock Winner in Tight Race for Governor] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110070148/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/networks-declare-bullock-winner-in-tight-race-for-governor/article_6e665ae8-252f-11e2-b495-001a4bcf887a.html |date=November 10, 2012 }}, ''The Billings Gazette'' by Charles S. Johnson. November 6, 2012. Retrieved November 7, 2012.</ref>  Bullock came out on top by 7,571 votes, or 48.9%, to Hill's 47.3%.  Libertarian candidate Ron Vandevender pulled 3.8% of the vote.<ref>Michael Barone, et al. ''The Almanac of American Politics 2014'' (2013) (Kindle Locations 48242-48245).</ref>\n\n===First term===\nGovernor Bullock and his lieutenant governor, John Walsh, were sworn in on January 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/local/bullock-invites-residents-to-inauguration-ceremony/article_b158f6d6-b734-5878-9018-a18a6251ab9a.html|title=Bullock invites residents to inauguration ceremony|work=Billings Gazette|accessdate=May 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110946/http://billingsgazette.com/news/local/bullock-invites-residents-to-inauguration-ceremony/article_b158f6d6-b734-5878-9018-a18a6251ab9a.html|archive-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock later appointed Walsh to become the new [[United States Senate|Senator]] from Montana to replace [[Max Baucus]], who had been appointed [[United States Ambassador to China|Ambassador to China]].  Bullock then appointed [[Angela McLean]] to replace Walsh as lieutenant governor.\n\nIn November 2015, McLean announced her resignation as lieutenant governor, effective upon the appointment of her successor, in order to accept the position of director of American Indian and minority achievement in the office of the state commissioner of higher education.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dennison |first=Mike |date=November 30, 2015 |title=Lt. Gov. McLean resigning to take higher-ed job |url=http://www.krtv.com/story/30630748/lt-gov-mclean-resigns-to-take-higher-ed-job |newspaper=KRTV-TV |location=Great Falls, MT |access-date=May 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043928/http://www.krtv.com/story/30630748/lt-gov-mclean-resigns-to-take-higher-ed-job |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Bullock announced the appointment of [[Mike Cooney]] as McLean's replacement. Cooney was sworn in on January 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://helenair.com/news/politics/mike-cooney-chosen-as-montana-s-next-lieutenant-governor/article_1d3bf1d1-2736-53e0-b6a2-d096a3d01ca6.html|title=Mike Cooney chosen as Montana's next lieutenant governor|author=Holly Michels|work=Helena Independent Record|accessdate=February 15, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303024055/http://helenair.com/news/politics/mike-cooney-chosen-as-montana-s-next-lieutenant-governor/article_1d3bf1d1-2736-53e0-b6a2-d096a3d01ca6.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a September 20, 2016, survey by ''[[Morning Consult]]'', Bullock, with a 66% approval rating and a 19% disapproval rating, was the most popular Democratic governor in the United States, as well as the fourth-most popular overall, behind Republicans [[Dennis Daugaard]] of [[Governor of South Dakota|South Dakota]], [[Larry Hogan]] of [[Governor of Maryland|Maryland]], and [[Charlie Baker]] of [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Troy|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/blogs/politics/morning-consult-bullock-approval-rating-at-percent/article_84013542-ed0a-5276-9650-912e3738bc56.html|title=Morning Consult: Bullock approval rating at 66 percent|work=[[Bozeman Daily Chronicle]]|date=September 20, 2016|accessdate=March 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617022324/http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/blogs/politics/morning-consult-bullock-approval-rating-at-percent/article_84013542-ed0a-5276-9650-912e3738bc56.html|archive-date=June 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\nBullock began his second term on January 2, 2017, alongside [[List of lieutenant governors of Montana|Montana Lieutenant Governor]] [[Mike Cooney]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Steve Bullock Sworn in as Montana\u2019s 24th Governor |url=http://governor.mt.gov/Newsroom/governor-steve-bullock-sworn-in-as-montanas-24th-governor |publisher=Office of Governor Steve Bullock |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904225832/http://governor.mt.gov/Newsroom/governor-steve-bullock-sworn-in-as-montanas-24th-governor |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock and Cooney were the only two Democrats to retain statewide offices in the 2016 elections as the Republicans captured the offices of [[Montana Office of Public Instruction|Montana Superintendent of Public Instruction]], [[Montana State Auditor]], and [[Montana Secretary of State]] and held onto the offices of [[Montana Attorney General]] and U.S. Representative for [[Montana's at-large congressional district]].<ref name=\"Bozeman Daily Chronicle\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Working together civilly is opening-day theme at Capitol |url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/mtleg/working-together-civilly-is-opening-day-theme-at-capitol/article_6665f579-595c-5aba-a286-ff858124449d.html |website=Bozeman Daily Chronicle |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Following the 2016 elections, Bullock faced large Republican majorities in the [[Montana Legislature]]. The Republicans gained three State Senate seats and widened their Senate majority over the Democrats to 32-18 while maintaining a 59-41 majority in the [[Montana House of Representatives]], the same as in 2015.<ref name=\"Bozeman Daily Chronicle\"/>\n\nIn the 2018 state legislative elections in Montana, Democrats won 42 of 100 seats in the [[Montana House of Representatives]] and gained two seats in the [[Montana Senate]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Montana Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-montana-elections.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> This meant that, in the 2019 state legislative session that Bullock presided over, Republicans held 60 percent of the seats in the upper chamber and 58 percent of the seats in the lower chamber of the [[Montana Legislature]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Drake |first1=Phil |title=Sine die: 66th legislative session is over |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2019/04/25/montana-legislature-adjourns/3577013002/ |website=Great Falls Tribune |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n[[File:Steve Bullock (48537192076).jpg|right|thumb|Bullock speaking at the 2019 Des Moines Register Soapbox at the Iowa State Fair.]]\n[[File:Steve Bullock 2020 presidential campaign logo.svg|thumb|right|200px|Bullock's 2020 presidential campaign logo]]\nIn 2017 Bullock formed the Big Sky Values PAC, which by spring 2019 had raised nearly $1.8 million, to pay for travel around the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Montana governor Steve Bullock to announce bid for presidency: report|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/441623-montana-governor-steve-bullock-to-announce-bid-for-presidency-report|access-date=May 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502231144/https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/441623-montana-governor-steve-bullock-to-announce-bid-for-presidency-report|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 14, 2019, Bullock announced his candidacy for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/steve-bullock-2020-montana-governor-running-for-president-watch-video-announcement-today-05-14-2019/|title=Steve Bullock, Montana governor, announces he's running for president|author=Camilo Montoya-Galvez|date=May 14, 2019|work=[[CBS]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514192140/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/steve-bullock-2020-montana-governor-running-for-president-watch-video-announcement-today-05-14-2019/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In his announcement video, Bullock said that opposing political \"[[dark money]]\" and legislating against the ''[[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United]]'' Supreme Court ruling would be among his utmost priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Raymond |last=Arke |authorlink   =|title= Opposed to \u2018dark money\u2019 and Citizens United, Montana Gov. Steve Bullock enters 2020 Democratic primary  |publisher=[[OpenSecrets.org]]|date=May 14, 2019 |url= https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2019/05/opposed-to-dark-money-and-citizens-united-montana-gov-steve-bullock-enters-2020-democratic-primary/ |accessdate=}}</ref> Based on his three statewide electoral victories in a largely rural state, Bullock held a certain cachet of \"electability\", and appeared to have a plausible path to the nomination.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/how-steve-bullock-could-win-the-2020-democratic-primary/ |title=How Steve Bullock Could Win The 2020 Democratic Primary |author=Rakich, Nathaniel |authorlink= |date=May 14, 2019 |publisher= |website=[[Fivethirtyeight.com]] |accessdate=December 4, 2019 |archiveurl= |archivedate= |url-status= }}</ref> His mid-May entrance was relatively late, but he was still able to qualify for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|second Democratic debate]] in July.<ref name=\"EpsteinStevens\">{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020-drops-out.html |title=Steve Bullock Drops Out of 2020 Presidential Race |author1=Epstein, Reid J. |author2=Stevens, Matt |date=December 2, 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |url-status= }}</ref> Even so, the late start left him with less media exposure than his numerous rivals: he found it hard to raise funds, and never rose above 1% in nationwide polls.<ref name=\"EpsteinStevens\"/> He ended his campaign on December 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weigel |first1=David |title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock drops out of presidential race |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-drops-out-of-presidential-race/2019/12/01/26c220ec-14a0-11ea-a659-7d69641c6ff7_story.html|website=Washington Post |accessdate=December 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==2020 Senate campaign==\n{{Main|2020 United States Senate election in Montana}}\nOn March 4, 2020, after months of speculation and denials from Bullock himself, the New York Times reported that Bullock would file in Montana's U.S. Senate [[2020 United States Senate election in Montana|election]] to challenge Republican incumbent [[Steve Daines]]. The move came after Senate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] (D-NY) personally flew to Montana to convince Bullock to run, and after Bullock talked with former president [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Steve Bullock Is Running for Senate in Montana|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/us/politics/steve-bullock-montana-senate.html|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> Both believed that he was the only formidable candidate against Daines.<ref>{{cite news|title= Schumer meets with Bullock as Montana filing deadline for Senate seat nears|url= https://www.politico.com/amp/news/2020/02/25/schumer-meets-bullock-montana-senate-seat-117479|last=Everett|first=Burgess|publisher=Politico|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2020}} Bullock is running for the seat formerly held for six terms by Democrat Max Baucus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-09/senior-adviser-montana-gov-steve-bullock-to-run-for-senate|title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock to run for Senate|date=2020-03-09|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> \n\nSteve Bullock officially declared his candidacy on March 9, 2020, which was the last day to file.<ref>https://twitter.com/stevebullockmt/status/1236986586606100481</ref> The announcement prompted all other candidates who were already running for the Democratic nomination except one to drop out and endorse Bullock. This included the mayor of Helena, [[Wilmot Collins]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Wilmot |title=Thank you, Montana. It's been my honor to run for U.S. Senate. Today I\u2019m suspending my campaign and endorsing Governor Steve Bullock. |url=https://twitter.com/CollinsWilmot/status/1237147675054600192 |website=@CollinsWilmot |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Neumann|first=Cora|title=Cora Neumann withdraws from Montana senate race, endorses Steve Bullock|url= https://mobile.twitter.com/CoraforMT/status/1237028772018180097|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref> https://mobile.twitter.com/KnolesMichael/status/1236997949730611207</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stein |first1=Perrin |title=Bozeman Senate candidate drops out of race, supports Bullock |url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/bozeman-senate-candidate-drops-out-of-race-supports-bullock/article_548ab9a5-c981-50c1-a3b4-044e0ec54df2.html |website=Bozeman Daily Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\nBullock has been described by ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[ABC News]]'' as a [[moderate Democrat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-considering-2020-white-house-bid-now-says-he-supports-assault-weapons-ban/2018/08/19/58f4a34c-a3f8-11e8-a656-943eefab5daf_story.html|title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock, considering 2020 White House bid, says he supports assault weapons ban|last=Sonmez|first=Felicia|date=August 19, 2018|website=washingtonpost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207091850/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-considering-2020-white-house-bid-now-says-he-supports-assault-weapons-ban/2018/08/19/58f4a34c-a3f8-11e8-a656-943eefab5daf_story.html|archive-date=December 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/red-state-governor-democrats-lose-midterms-referendum-donald/story?id=57477278|title=Democratic governor of Montana says 'no secret recipe' as he eyes 2020|date=August 29, 2018|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=December 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124148/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/red-state-governor-democrats-lose-midterms-referendum-donald/story?id=57477278|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to Bullock as being among [[Centrism|centrist]] Democratic governors.<ref name=NYTimes17July2017>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/17/us/politics/democrat-governors-bullock-mcauliffe.html|title=As Party Drifts Left, Pragmatic Democratic Governors Have Eye on White House|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=July 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 8, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129073634/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/17/us/politics/democrat-governors-bullock-mcauliffe.html|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The non-partisan organization, [[On the Issues|On The Issues]], which tracks candidates' positions and records, considers Bullock to be a \"Moderate Liberal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Steve_Bullock.htm|title=Steve Bullock on the Issues|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107202331/http://www.ontheissues.org/Steve_Bullock.htm|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nBullock is pro-choice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Decides? The Status Of Women's Reproductive Rights in the United States|date=February 6, 2018|url=https://www.prochoiceamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/WhoDecides2018-withCover-1.pdf|website=NARAL|publisher=NARAL: Pro-Choice America|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427045435/https://www.prochoiceamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/WhoDecides2018-withCover-1.pdf|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During the 2017 state legislative session, Bullock vetoed two bills (SB 282, SB 329) aimed at restricting late-term abortions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flatheadbeacon.com/2017/05/02/passed-failed-montana-legislature/|title=What Passed and What Failed at the Montana Legislature|last=Scott|first=Tristan|date=May 2, 2017|work=Flathead Beacon|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075828/https://flatheadbeacon.com/2017/05/02/passed-failed-montana-legislature/|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Governor Bullock Stands With Montana Families By Vetoing Extreme Bills Endangering Women|url=https://www.aclumontana.org/en/press-releases/governor-bullock-stands-montana-families-vetoing-extreme-bills-endangering-women|website=American Civil Liberties Union of Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702093732/https://www.aclumontana.org/en/press-releases/governor-bullock-stands-montana-families-vetoing-extreme-bills-endangering-women|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock received a 100 percent rating from [[NARAL]] in 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Bullock's Ratings and Endorsements|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/110899/steve-bullock#.Wzm38NhKjOQ|website=Vote Smart: Facts Matter|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702093326/https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/110899/steve-bullock#.Wzm38NhKjOQ|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was endorsed by [[Planned Parenthood]] Advocates of Montana in his successful 2016 reelection bid.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stahl|first1=Martha|title=Big Sky Impact: Election Recap|url=https://www.plannedparenthood.org/uploads/filer_public/dd/3c/dd3c6ace-071c-4b50-9bae-cde793dfea69/pp_winternews2016-17_web.pdf|website=Planned Parenthood Advocates of Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516235247/https://www.plannedparenthood.org/uploads/filer_public/dd/3c/dd3c6ace-071c-4b50-9bae-cde793dfea69/pp_winternews2016-17_web.pdf|archive-date=May 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was one of 14 Democratic governors to write a letter to [[Alex Azar]], President Trump's [[Secretary of Health and Human Services]], on March 31, 2018 demanding that Title X funding for women's reproductive health care and family planning remain in effect. The 14 governors threatened legal action if the Trump administration were to undermine women's access to reproductive health care.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Inslee|first1=Jay|title=Letter to Alex Azar|url=https://democraticgovernors.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/DGA-Letter-Title-X.pdf|website=Democratic Governors Association|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215212821/https://democraticgovernors.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/DGA-Letter-Title-X.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Campaign finance reform===\nAs Attorney General of Montana, Bullock advocated on behalf of the state's century-old ban on corporate money in elections, the [[Montana Corrupt Practices Act of 1912]]. After that and similar laws were struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court's ''[[Citizens United]]'' decision in 2010, Bullock countered with a new case, ''American Tradition Partnership, Inc. v. Bullock'' (2012). Although the Supreme Court disposed of the case in a 5-4 decision,<ref>{{cite web |title=AMERICAN TRADITION PARTNERSHIP, INC. v. BULLOCK |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/11-1179 |website=Legal Information Institute |publisher=Cornell Law School |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192224/https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/11-1179 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bullock continued to advocate for campaign finance reform throughout his time as Governor of Montana.<ref name=\"Billings Gazette\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Bullock signs Montana campaign finance bill into law |url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/bullock-signs-montana-campaign-finance-bill-into-law/article_c8a0cc59-a7bf-5381-9136-ae118d9a13ff.html |website=Billings Gazette |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904191908/https://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/bullock-signs-montana-campaign-finance-bill-into-law/article_c8a0cc59-a7bf-5381-9136-ae118d9a13ff.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Memoli |first1=Mike |title=Montana governor pushes for more transparency on donors |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/card/montana-governor-pushes-more-transparency-donors-n880316 |website=NBC News |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905052524/https://www.nbcnews.com/card/montana-governor-pushes-more-transparency-donors-n880316 |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bullock steered the DISCLOSE Act, a bipartisan campaign finance reform bill that bolstered disclosure requirements in Montana elections, through a GOP-controlled state legislature.<ref name=\"Billings Gazette\"/><ref>{{Cite AV media |people=Soboroff, Jacob |title=MSNBC's American Swamp: Governor Bullock leading the fight against dark money in politics |medium=Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uyL2h8e0CNI |publisher=Steve Bullock <!-- Official YouTube account --> |location= |date=July 29, 2019 |time= }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bullock signed an executive order that required the recipients of major government contracts in Montana to disclose \"[[dark money]] spending\" in elections, including spending disclosure that is not explicitly required by federal law.<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=Bullock tells Montana contractors to report \u2018dark money\u2019 |url=https://coloradopolitics.com/out-west-roundup-bullock-tells-montana-contractors-report-dark-money/ |website=CP: Colorado Politics |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192022/https://coloradopolitics.com/out-west-roundup-bullock-tells-montana-contractors-report-dark-money/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2018, Bullock sued the Internal Revenue Service and the U.S. Department of the Treasury<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanson |first1=Amy Beth |title=Montana governor sues over IRS policy on tax-exempt groups |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/montana-governor-sues-over-irs-policy-on-tax-exempt-groups/ |website=Seattle Times |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192246/https://www.seattletimes.com/business/montana-governor-sues-over-irs-policy-on-tax-exempt-groups/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> over a recent decision to dispense with donor requirements for nonprofit organizations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lorenzo |first1=Aaron |title=Treasury defends move to halt nonprofit disclosures amid Wyden threat |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/17/treasury-nonprofit-donor-disclosures-690200 |website=Politico |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903140946/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/17/treasury-nonprofit-donor-disclosures-690200 |archive-date=September 3, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Climate change and environment===\nBullock believes that climate change is real and that humans contribute to it,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hegyi |first1=Nate |title=Montana Governor Says Ignoring Climate Change Is 'Shortsighted And Dangerous' |url=https://www.mtpr.org/post/montana-governor-says-ignoring-climate-change-shortsighted-and-dangerous |website=Montana Public Radio |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514170114/https://www.mtpr.org/post/montana-governor-says-ignoring-climate-change-shortsighted-and-dangerous |archive-date=May 14, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last1=Harball |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Beck |first2=Madelyn |title=Obama climate rule looms large in Mont. governor's race |url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060033730 |website=E&E News |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515141541/http://www.eenews.net/stories/1060033730 |archive-date=May 15, 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> but Montana became the first state to halt preparations for the [[Clean Power Plan]] when the [[United States Supreme Court]] announced a stay of the plan in February 2016.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIn September 2014, Bullock signed an executive order creating a habitat conservation plan for [[Centrocercus|sage-grouse]] in a bid to keep management of the imperiled bird in state hands rather than see it come under federal Endangered Species Act protection. The government said to the press: \"Montanans recognize that it is in the best interest of our state, its economy and our quality of life to maintain state management of the greater sage-grouse.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zuckermann|first1=Laura|title=Montana governor issues sage grouse conservation plan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/10/us-usa-sagegrouse-montana-idUSKBN0H502420140910|accessdate=September 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913094616/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/10/us-usa-sagegrouse-montana-idUSKBN0H502420140910|archive-date=September 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2019, Bullock was the only remaining 2020 Democratic presidential candidate who had not yet signed the No Fossil Fuel Money pledge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nofossilfuelmoney.org/presidential-signers/|title=Pledge Signers - Presidential|work=No Fossil Fuel Money Pledge|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic Party===\nBullock endorsed [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 general election]] but expressed disagreement with Clinton's opposition to coal mining because it is an important industry in Montana. He did not attend the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]], citing his duties as [[Governor of Montana]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Retana|first1=Judith|title=Bullock will not attend DNC, still endorses Clinton|url=http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/bullock-will-not-attend-dnc-still-endorses-clinton|website=NBC Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703021825/http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/bullock-will-not-attend-dnc-still-endorses-clinton|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock appears to have stayed neutral during the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hillary Endorsements - The 5 GOVs She Needs For a Sweep (OT Update: Donna Edwards has endorsed HRC)|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/17/1450543/-Hillary-Endorsements-The-5-GOVs-She-Needs-For-a-Sweep|website=Daily Kos|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702204814/https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/17/1450543/-Hillary-Endorsements-The-5-GOVs-She-Needs-For-a-Sweep|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was chairman of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] in 2015, overseeing the [[2015 Louisiana gubernatorial election|election]] of Gov. [[John Bel Edwards]] of [[Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=DGA Chair Governor Steve Bullock's Statement on Louisiana Victory|url=https://democraticgovernors.org/news/dga-chair-governor-steve-bullocks-statement-on-louisiana-victory|website=Democratic Governors Association|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090004/https://democraticgovernors.org/news/dga-chair-governor-steve-bullocks-statement-on-louisiana-victory/|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> a pro-life [[Southern Democrat]] who expanded Medicaid to more than 471,000 Louisianans and reformed his state's criminal justice system  after winning the [[Governor of Louisiana|governorship]] of a heavily Republican state.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Crisp|first1=Elizabeth|title=Poll: Louisiana residents view Medicaid expansion, criminal justice changes favorably|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/politics/legislature/article_08d336ca-3f45-11e8-bb7f-fb5c1c1a0b96.html|website=The Advocate (Baton Rouge, LA)|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702233147/https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/politics/legislature/article_08d336ca-3f45-11e8-bb7f-fb5c1c1a0b96.html|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Bullock expressed that there are \"roles for all of us [Democrats]\" within the party, referring to liberal, moderate, and conservative Democrats alike.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cheney|first1=Kyle|last2=Pradhan|first2=Rachana|title=Red-state Democrats fret about leftward shift|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/red-state-democrats-leftward-shift-120605|website=Politico: Elections|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703021817/https://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/red-state-democrats-leftward-shift-120605|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was one of just three Democrats to win gubernatorial elections in 2016 in states that President Trump carried that year (one of whom, [[Jim Justice]], is now a Republican), and the only incumbent Democratic governor to win re-election in a state that Trump carried.<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=2016 Governor Election Results |url=https://www.politico.com/mapdata-2016/2016-election/results/map/governor/ |website=Politico |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064031/https://www.politico.com/mapdata-2016/2016-election/results/map/governor/ |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was also one of the few Democratic incumbents besides [[North Carolina State Auditor]] [[Beth Wood]],<ref>{{cite web |title=North Carolina Auditor Results: Beth Wood Leads |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina-auditor |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064122/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina-auditor |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[North Carolina Secretary of State]] [[Elaine Marshall]],<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=North Carolina Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina |website=The New York Times |access-date=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705210333/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina |archive-date=July 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> West Virginia State Treasurer [[John Perdue]],<ref>{{cite web |title=West Virginia Treasurer Results: John Perdue Wins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/west-virginia-treasurer |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034646/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/west-virginia-treasurer |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and [[Pennsylvania Auditor General]] [[Eugene DePasquale]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania Auditor General Results: Eugene DePasquale Wins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/pennsylvania-auditor-general |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034637/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/pennsylvania-auditor-general |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> to win re-election to statewide offices in states that President Trump won in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].\n\nSince the [[2016 United States elections|2016 elections]], in which Democrats lost the [[2016 United States presidential election|presidency]], ceded control of several [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2016|governorships]], and came short of winning majorities in the [[2016 United States Senate elections|U.S. Senate]] and [[2016 United States House of Representatives elections|U.S. House of Representatives]], Bullock has publicly argued that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] needs to expand its reach beyond urban areas and the nation's two coasts. He has encouraged Democrats to engage with and attempt to persuade voters in suburban and rural areas rather than relying solely on base turnout.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=May 16, 2017 CAP Ideas Conference: Gov. Steve Bullock (D-MT)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iu73mHdRrYk|website=Center for American Progress|publisher=Center for American Progress|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090100/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iu73mHdRrYk|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=How Democrats Can Win in the West|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/opinion/steve-bullock-democrats-montana.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702211936/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/opinion/steve-bullock-democrats-montana.html|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He  visited Iowa,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Volz|first1=Matt|title=Gov. Bullock travels to Iowa as he explores possible 2020 run for president|url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/04/06/montana-governor-travels-iowa-he-explores-possible-presidential-run-steve-bullock/495026002|website=Great Falls Tribune|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Wisconsin,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Charles|title=Possible 2020 presidential candidate Steve Bullock visits Milwaukee|url=https://www.tmj4.com/news/local-news/possible-2020-presidential-candidate-steve-bullock-visits-milwaukee|website=Today's TMJ-4: WTMJ-TV Milwaukee|publisher=Scripps TV Station Group|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627033943/https://www.tmj4.com/news/local-news/possible-2020-presidential-candidate-steve-bullock-visits-milwaukee|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Colorado<ref>{{cite web|last1=Luning|first1=Ernest|title=Montana Governor Steve Bullock tapped to keynote Colorado Democrats\u2019 annual dinner|url=https://coloradopolitics.com/montana-governor-steve-bullock-tapped-keynote-colorado-democrats-annual-dinner|website=Colorado Politics|publisher=Colorado Politics|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702204551/https://coloradopolitics.com/montana-governor-steve-bullock-tapped-keynote-colorado-democrats-annual-dinner/|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> to campaign for and speak in support of Democratic candidates during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 election cycle]], which saw Democrats retake the majority in the U.S. House and gain governorships and state legislature seats. Bullock's visits around the country led some to speculate that he was considering a run for [[President of the United States]], which turned out to be true when he announced his candidacy for president on May 14, 2019.<ref>State of the Union, Jake Tapper, CNN August 19, 2018</ref>\n\n===Death penalty===\nIn 2019, Bullock said he supports the [[death penalty]] in \u201climited circumstances\u201d like terrorism \u2014 a stance that distinguished the former state attorney general from the crowded 2020 Democratic presidential field.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/jun/19/steve-bullock-supports-death-penalty-limited-circu/|title=Steve Bullock supports death penalty in \u2018limited\u2019 circumstances|work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\nUntil at least 2016, Bullock opposed [[gun control]] and [[universal background checks]] and stated that as governor \"our [[Second Amendment]] rights have been expanded in Montana.\u201d<ref name=NYTimes14May2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/14/us/politics/steve-bullock-on-the-issues.html?searchResultPosition=2 |title=Where Steve Bullock Stands on the Issues|last=Astor|first=Maggie|date=May 14, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 31, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2018, he changed his positions to support [[universal background checks]], limits on [[High-capacity magazine|magazine sizes]], temporary removal of firearms from potentially violent people ([[red flag laws]]), and  banning certain types of [[Semi-automatic firearm|\"semiautomatic weapons\"]].<ref name=NYTimes14May2019/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nBullock expanded [[Medicaid]] coverage in Montana under the [[Affordable Care Act]] with a Republican-dominated state legislature. He is in favor of expanding accessibility to healthcare and trying to protect, improve, and strengthen the Affordable Care Act and does not favor a [[single-payer system]].<ref name=NYTimes17July2017/><ref name=NYTimes14May2019/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020-campaign.html?searchResultPosition=6#health |title=Meet the Candidates: 18 Questions. 21 Democrats. Here\u2019s What They Said.|date=2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 31, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nThen-Attorney General Steve Bullock opposed a 2012 voter-approved law in the State of Montana, Legislative Referendum 121, that would have required state agencies to verify through a federal database whether individuals requesting certain services were U.S. citizens.<ref name=\"USA Todat\">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=John S. |title=Court strikes down Montana immigration law |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/23/court-strikes-montana-immigration-law/11276379/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904231232/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/23/court-strikes-montana-immigration-law/11276379/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The law, which had been intended to deny government jobs and assistance to undocumented immigrants, was ruled unconstitutional and legally unenforceable.<ref name=\"USA Todat\"/>\n\nDespite pushback from Republican state legislators, Governor Bullock supported allowing Syrian refugees to resettle in the State of Montana in 2015, but promised that ensuring the safety of Montanans would be his \"top priority\" during the resettlement process.<ref name=\"Missoulian\">{{cite web |last1=Michels |first1=Holly |title=[UPDATED] 55 legislators tell Bullock to block Syrian refugees |url=https://missoulian.com/helena/news/politics/state/updated-legislators-tell-bullock-to-block-syrian-refugees/article_0dcdcbd2-1e97-596b-be7c-2bac2478003a.html |website=Missoulian |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192159/https://missoulian.com/helena/news/politics/state/updated-legislators-tell-bullock-to-block-syrian-refugees/article_0dcdcbd2-1e97-596b-be7c-2bac2478003a.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> At least 31 other governors at the time opposed the resettlement of Syrian refugees.<ref name=\"Missoulian\"/>\n\nBullock supports the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program and signed a letter on September 7, 2017, alongside 10 other governors to congressional leaders in support of legislation that would protect DACA recipients and \"take immediate action to ensure that these young people can continue to live, work, and contribute to the country they have called home for most of their lives.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Tara |title=11 governors urge Congress to take immediate action to protect DACA recipients |url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/11-governors-urge-congress-take-immediate-action-protect-daca-recipients |website=Washington Governor Jay Inslee |publisher=State of Washington |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904193136/https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/11-governors-urge-congress-take-immediate-action-protect-daca-recipients |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2018, Bullock refused to deploy National Guard troops from Montana to the Mexican border \"based simply on the whim of the President's morning Twitter habit\".<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=Bullock says no to Guard deployment based on Trump's 'whim' |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/04/05/bullock-says-no-guard-deployment-based-trumps-whim/491796002/ |website=Great Falls Tribune |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Bullock voiced strong opposition to the Trump administration's policy of family separations at the Mexican border, and said in a statement: \"As a governor and a father, I'm disgusted. I don't care if it's the President or Congress \u2013 these atrocities must end immediately.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Inslee |first1=Jay (Chair) |title=VIDEO: Dem Govs Lead Pushback to Trump on Child Separation Crisis |url=https://democraticgovernors.org/news/video-dem-govs-lead-pushback-to-trump-on-child-separation-crisis/ |website=Democratic Governors Association |publisher=Democratic Governors Association |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090107/https://democraticgovernors.org/news/video-dem-govs-lead-pushback-to-trump-on-child-separation-crisis/ |archive-date=April 27, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage===\nBullock supports [[same-sex marriage]], and praised the federal judge who struck down Montana's same-sex marriage ban in 2014, making Montana the 34th U.S. state to legalize same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Whitcomb |first1=Dan |title=U.S. judge strikes down Montana's gay marriage ban |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-gaymarriage-montana-idUSKCN0J32FL20141119 |website=Reuters: U.S. |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719061628/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-gaymarriage-montana-idUSKCN0J32FL20141119 |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He also supported the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', which legalized same-sex marriage nationwide, and said in a statement on June 26, 2015: \u201cThis ruling protects the right of all Montanans to marry the person they love, and moves our state and nation closer to the promise of freedom, dignity, and equality that they were founded upon. All people, regardless of their sexual orientation, should have the opportunity to make a good life for themselves and their families.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Dave |title=BULLOCK STATEMENT ON MARRIAGE EQUALITY RULING |url=https://news.mt.gov/bullock-statement-on-marriage-equality-ruling |website=Montana.Gov: Official State Website |publisher=State of Montana |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054238/https://news.mt.gov/bullock-statement-on-marriage-equality-ruling |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock has also spoken at Pride rallies in Montana,<ref>{{cite web |title=Acceptance and equality focus of Big Sky Pride Rally |url=http://www.kxlh.com/story/32254139/acceptance-and-equality-focus-of-big-sky-pride-rally |website=9KXLH.com: Montana's News Leader, Helena and Central Montana |publisher=Cordillera Communications |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054536/http://www.kxlh.com/story/32254139/acceptance-and-equality-focus-of-big-sky-pride-rally |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kuglin |first1=Tom |title='Show them our hearts': Big Sky Pride marks 25th year with parade and rally in Helena |url=https://helenair.com/news/local/show-them-our-hearts-big-sky-pride-marks-th-year/article_63b80587-a843-5288-8908-3ec8c973542f.html |website=Helena Independent Record |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719083733/https://helenair.com/news/local/show-them-our-hearts-big-sky-pride-marks-th-year/article_63b80587-a843-5288-8908-3ec8c973542f.html |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and, in 2015, became the first sitting governor in Montana history to officiate a same-sex wedding.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Drake |first1=Phil |title=Bullock first Montana governor to officiate same-sex wedding |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2015/10/23/bullock-1st-montana-gov-officiate-same-sex-wedding/74456124/|website=Great Falls Tribune |accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Bullock enacted an executive order that prohibits state agencies, state contractors, and subcontractors, from  discriminating in employment on the basis of sexual orientation or [[gender identity]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dehaven |first1=James |title=Bullock expands discrimination ban to cover gender identity, military service, pregnancy |url=https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-expands-discrimination-ban-to-cover-gender-identity-military-service/article_ab153e85-762f-58ce-a7ba-d556ac49f564.html |website=Missoulian |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054753/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-expands-discrimination-ban-to-cover-gender-identity-military-service/article_ab153e85-762f-58ce-a7ba-d556ac49f564.html |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The executive order expanded upon a previous one signed by former Governor [[Brian Schweitzer]] in 2008, which had similar goals but did not include protections for gender identity and did not apply to contractors or subcontractors.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Metzger |first1=Ianthe |title=Montana Gov Steve Bullock Signs Executive Order Protecting LGBT State Employees |url=https://www.hrc.org/blog/montana-governor-steve-bullock-signs-executive-order-protecting-lgbt-state |website=Human Rights Campaign |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715104920/http://www.hrc.org/blog/montana-governor-steve-bullock-signs-executive-order-protecting-lgbt-state |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Net neutrality===\nBullock supports [[net neutrality]] and opposed the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s decision to repeal net neutrality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lecher |first1=Colin |title=Montana governor signs executive order to keep net neutrality in the state |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16920192/montana-governor-net-neutrality-executive-order |website=The Verge |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905141049/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16920192/montana-governor-net-neutrality-executive-order |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On January 22, 2018, Bullock signed an executive order prohibiting any internet service provider with a state government contract from blocking or charging additional fees for faster delivery of websites, two major principles of net neutrality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kang |first1=Cecelia |title=Montana Governor Signs Order to Force Net Neutrality |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/22/technology/montana-net-neutrality.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904205107/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/22/technology/montana-net-neutrality.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Through this executive order, Montana became the first state to implement and enforce net neutrality after the FCC repeal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neidig |first1=Harper |title=Montana becomes first state to implement net neutrality after FCC repeal |url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/370133-montana-becomes-first-state-to-implement-net-neutrality-rules-following-fcc |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102120/http://thehill.com/policy/technology/370133-montana-becomes-first-state-to-implement-net-neutrality-rules-following-fcc |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The governors of [[New York (state)|New York]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Governor Cuomo Signs Executive Order to Protect and Strengthen Net Neutrality in New York |url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-signs-executive-order-protect-and-strengthen-net-neutrality-new-york |website=Office of Governor Andrew M. Cuomo |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102201/https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-signs-executive-order-protect-and-strengthen-net-neutrality-new-york |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neidig |first1=Harper |title=New Jersey governor signs net neutrality order |url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/372409-new-jersey-governor-signs-net-neutrality-order |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corporation |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102107/http://thehill.com/policy/technology/372409-new-jersey-governor-signs-net-neutrality-order |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Vermont]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Kieren |title=Vermont becomes fifth US state to boot up its own net neutrality rules |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/02/16/vermont_net_neutrality_rules/ |website=The Register |publisher=Situation Publishing |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905175614/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/02/16/vermont_net_neutrality_rules/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Hawaii]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leong |first1=Jodi |last2=McMillan |first2=Cindy |title=GOVERNOR IGE SIGNS EXECUTIVE ORDER TO PROTECT NET NEUTRALITY IN HAWAI\u2018I |url=https://governor.hawaii.gov/newsroom/latest-news/governor-ige-signs-executive-order-to-protect-net-neutrality-in-hawaii/ |website=State of Hawaii |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102151/https://governor.hawaii.gov/newsroom/latest-news/governor-ige-signs-executive-order-to-protect-net-neutrality-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and [[Rhode Island]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Patrick |title=Raimondo orders state agencies to use internet providers that observe net neutrality |url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180424/raimondo-orders-state-agencies-to-use-internet-providers-that-observe-net-neutrality |website=Providence Journal|accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905142605/http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180424/raimondo-orders-state-agencies-to-use-internet-providers-that-observe-net-neutrality |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> eventually followed suit.\n\n===Organized labor===\nBullock has been recognized and endorsed by the [[American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (AFL-CIO),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calvan |first1=Bobby Caina |title=AFL-CIO leader vows union support for Bullock, Juneau |url=https://www.apnews.com/bd61c5b2e69a4b4897db06523f0b161f |website=Associated Press |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192042/https://www.apnews.com/bd61c5b2e69a4b4897db06523f0b161f |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and by the Montana Education Association - Montana Federation of Teachers,<ref>{{cite web |last1=P\u00e9rez |first1=F\u00e9lix |title=Governors races in MO, MT and NC put spotlight on students, educators |url=https://educationvotes.nea.org/2016/08/26/governors-races-mo-mt-nc-put-spotlight-students-educators/ |website=Education Votes |publisher=National Education Association |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904191958/https://educationvotes.nea.org/2016/08/26/governors-races-mo-mt-nc-put-spotlight-students-educators/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> for his support of worker's rights and public education.\n\nBullock opposes right-to-work legislation,<ref name=\"billingsgazette.com\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Bullock seeks governor\u2019s office vowing to create jobs, protect union rights |url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-seeks-governor-s-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect/article_7656c3e3-9820-587c-accf-f2e282daf128.html |website=Billings Gazette |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904225714/https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-seeks-governor-s-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect/article_7656c3e3-9820-587c-accf-f2e282daf128.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> which allows workers to forgo paying union dues while still benefitting from union-negotiated labor contracts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Elizabeth G. |title=What right-to-work laws really mean |url=http://fortune.com/2012/01/31/what-right-to-work-laws-really-mean/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192005/http://fortune.com/2012/01/31/what-right-to-work-laws-really-mean/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Montana is the only state in the Upper Rocky Mountain region of the U.S. that does not have right-to-work legislation in place, and all of its neighboring states do not provide the same level of protection for labor unions.<ref name=\"billingsgazette.com\"/>\n\nOn January 18, 2018, Bullock filed an amicus brief to the U.S. Supreme Court in support of allowing labor unions to make \"agency fees\" mandatory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennison |first1=Mike |title=Gov. Bullock tells U.S. Supreme Court to preserve labor union `agency fees\u2019 |url=http://www.krtv.com/story/37305577/gov-bullock-tells-us-supreme-court-to-preserve-labor-union-agency-fees |website=KRTV.com |publisher=Cordillera Communications |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904193718/http://www.krtv.com/story/37305577/gov-bullock-tells-us-supreme-court-to-preserve-labor-union-agency-fees |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock opposed the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Janus v. AFSCME]]'', and said in a statement: \"The US Supreme Court just overturned 40 years of settled law that workers, employers and unions across the country rely on. All the more ironic, the 5-4 decision cited ''Citizens United'' as a reason to do so.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MT officials react to Supreme Court organized labor ruling |url=https://nbcmontana.com/news/local/mt-officials-react-to-supreme-court-organized-labor-ruling |website=NBC Montana |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192118/https://nbcmontana.com/news/local/mt-officials-react-to-supreme-court-organized-labor-ruling |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Steve Bullock}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Dark Money (film)|Dark Money]]'' (film)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://governor.mt.gov/ Governor Steve Bullock's official Montana government website]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Montana/Government/Executive/Governor_Steve_Bullock|Steve Bullock}}\n* {{C-SPAN|stevebullock02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike McGrath]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]]|years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tim Fox (politician)|Tim Fox]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Schweitzer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]]|years=[[Montana gubernatorial election, 2012|2012]], [[Montana gubernatorial election, 2016|2016]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Shumlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dannel Malloy|Dan Malloy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Schweitzer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Sandoval]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[National Governors Association]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Larry Hogan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Montana}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br>{{nowrap|''as {{small|[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kristi Noem]]|as=[[Governor of South Dakota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Montana}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jay Inslee]]|as=[[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{Current Montana statewide political officials}}\n{{Governors of Montana}}\n{{Current U.S. governors}}\n{{National Governors Association chairs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bullock, Steve}}\n[[Category:Steve Bullock| ]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Claremont McKenna College alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:Governors of Montana]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Montana Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Montana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Missoula, Montana]]\n[[Category:American gun control activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Steve Bullock}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|24th Governor of Montana}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Steve Bullock\n| image = Steve Bullock by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| order = 24th [[List of governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]]\n| lieutenant = [[John Walsh (U.S. senator)|John Walsh]]<br>[[Angela McLean]]<br>[[Mike Cooney]]\n| term_start = January 7, 2013\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Brian Schweitzer]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = Chair of the [[National Governors Association]]\n| term_start1 = July 21, 2018\n| term_end1 = July 26, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Brian Sandoval]]\n| successor1 = [[Larry Hogan]]\n| office2 = 23rd [[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]]\n| governor2 = Brian Schweitzer\n| term_start2 = January 5, 2009\n| term_end2 = January 7, 2013\n| predecessor2 = [[Mike McGrath]]\n| successor2 = [[Tim Fox (politician)|Tim Fox]]\n| birth_name = Stephen Clark Bullock\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Missoula, Montana]], U.S.\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lisa Downs|1999}}\n| children = 3<ref>{{cite web |url=https://biographytree.com/biography/lisa-bullock-biography-wife-governor-steve-bullock |title=Lisa Bullock Biography - Wife of Governor Steve Bullock |date=March 28, 2017 |website=Biographytree.com |accessdate=July 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013111/https://biographytree.com/biography/lisa-bullock-biography-wife-governor-steve-bullock/|archive-date=July 17, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| residence = [[Montana Governor's Residence|Governor's Residence]]\n| education = [[Claremont McKenna College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Columbia University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| signature = Bullock sig.png\n}}\n'''Stephen Clark Bullock''' (born April 11, 1966) is an American politician, lawyer, and former professor serving as the [[List of Governors of Montana|24th]] and current [[List of Governors of Montana|Governor of Montana]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\nBorn in [[Missoula, Montana]], Bullock graduated from [[Claremont McKenna College]] and [[Columbia Law School]].  He began his career working as legal counsel to the [[Secretary of State of Montana]] before becoming the Executive Assistant Attorney General and acting Chief Deputy Attorney General of Montana. Bullock then entered private practice as an lawyer for [[Steptoe & Johnson]]. He was an adjunct professor at the [[George Washington University Law School]] before opening his own law firm upon returning to Montana. In 2008, Bullock was elected [[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]], and he served one term from 2009 to 2013.\n\nBullock declared his candidacy for Governor of Montana on September 7, 2011. The seat was open in 2012, as incumbent Governor [[Brian Schweitzer]], a Democrat, could not seek reelection due to term limits. Bullock won the Democratic primary with 87% of the vote and defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Rick Hill]] in the [[2012 Montana gubernatorial election|general election]] with 48% of the vote. In [[2016 Montana gubernatorial election|2016]], Bullock won re-election with 50.2% of the vote, defeating [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee [[Greg Gianforte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/11/28/elizabeth-warren-and-9-other-democrats-i-left-off-my-2020-presidential-list|title=Why I left Elizabeth Warren off my 2020 presidential list (and why I was wrong)|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603193443/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/11/28/elizabeth-warren-and-9-other-democrats-i-left-off-my-2020-presidential-list/|archive-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/23/opinion/red-state-hope-for-democratic-blues.html|title=Red State Hope for Democratic Blues|first=Timothy|last=Egan|date=December 23, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2017|via=NYTimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819022144/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/23/opinion/red-state-hope-for-democratic-blues.html|archive-date=August 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock chaired the [[National Governors Association]] from 2018 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=State of Montana |title=Governor Steve Bullock |accessdate=July 20, 2018 |url=http://governor.mt.gov/Home/Governor |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225438/http://governor.mt.gov/Home/Governor |archive-date=July 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hanson |first=Amy Beth |publisher=Flathead Beacon |title=Bullock Outlines Jobs Initiative for Governors Association |date=July 16, 2018 |accessdate=July 20, 2018 |url=https://flatheadbeacon.com/2018/07/16/bullock-outlines-jobs-initiative-governors-association/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225350/https://flatheadbeacon.com/2018/07/16/bullock-outlines-jobs-initiative-governors-association/ |archive-date=July 20, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was a [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic candidate]] for [[President of the United States]] in [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]].<ref>{{cite tweet |title=To give everyone a fair shot, we must do more than defeat Donald Trump. We have to defeat the corrupt system that keeps people like him in power, and we need a fighter who's done it before. That's why I'm running for President. Join our team: http://stevebullock.com |number=1128238526330359808|date=14 May 2019|user=GovernorBullock|author=Steve Bullock}}</ref> After suspending his presidential campaign, he announced his candidacy for the [[United States Senate]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Montana|2020 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/9/21166028/steve-bullock-montana-senate-race-democrats|title=Gov. Steve Bullock just made the Montana Senate race competitive for Democrats|publisher=Vox|date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nBullock was born in [[Missoula, Montana]], and raised in [[Helena, Montana|Helena]], the state capital. He is the son of Penny Clark, a school board trustee, and Mike Bullock, a teacher and administrator.<ref>[http://stevebullock.com/bullock-seeks-governors-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect-union-rights \"Bullock vows to create jobs and protect union rights\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20141119000616/http://stevebullock.com/bullock-seeks-governors-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect-union-rights|date=November 19, 2014}}, stevebullock.com; accessed September 17, 2015.</ref> He graduated from [[Helena High School]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801200809/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=August 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was in grade school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-fox-go-toe-to-toe-in-attorney-general-race/article_84f43fff-4029-5e77-af07-c1d2ca51db4b.html|title=Bullock, Fox go toe-to-toe in attorney general race|last=McKee|first=Jennifer|work=The Billings Gazette|access-date=September 21, 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034454/https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-fox-go-toe-to-toe-in-attorney-general-race/article_84f43fff-4029-5e77-af07-c1d2ca51db4b.html|archive-date=September 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock received his B.A. degree in Politics, Philosophy, and Economics from [[Claremont McKenna College]] and his J.D. degree with honors from [[Columbia Law School]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock profile|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801200809/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=August 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tsl.news/steve-bullock-montana-governor-president/ |title=Q&A: Montana Gov. Steve Bullock CM \u201988 on college experience, potential presidential run  |access-date=April 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430151555/https://tsl.news/steve-bullock-montana-governor-president/ |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bullock served as chief legal counsel to [[Secretary of State of Montana|Montana Secretary of State]] [[Mike Cooney]]. He went on to work for four years with the Montana Department of Justice under Attorney General Joe Mazurek, first as executive assistant attorney general, and later as acting chief deputy (1997\u20132001).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Attorney General Steve Bullock|url=https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730231720/https://doj.mt.gov/our-attorney-general/|archive-date=July 30, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> During this time, he also served as legislative director, coordinating the Attorney General's legislative efforts. As an Assistant Attorney General, Bullock wrote the landmark opinion that guaranteed public access to streams and rivers.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nHe was unsuccessful in his first race for Montana Attorney General, losing in the 2000 Democratic primary to [[Mike McGrath]], who went on to be elected Attorney General that year and currently serves as Chief Justice of the [[Montana Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 Statewide General Canvass|url=http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2000/2000Prim/2000-PrimState.pdf|publisher=Montana Secretary of State|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228155901/http://sos.mt.gov/Elections/Archives/2000s/2000/2000Prim/2000-PrimState.pdf|archivedate=December 28, 2013}}</ref> From 2001 to 2004, Bullock practiced law in Washington, D.C., with Steptoe & Johnson, where he served as an adjunct professor at George Washington University Law School. He returned to Montana in 2004, working in private practice in Helena where he represented individuals, consumer organizations, labor unions, peace officers, associations of political subdivisions, as well as small and large businesses.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Attorney General==\nBullock was the Democratic nominee for Attorney General in 2008, defeating two other candidates in the primary election in June. He went on to win the contested general election race with 52.64% of the vote against Republican Tim Fox. Bullock received 245,669 votes, more than either other candidate.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=2008 Statewide General Canvass|url=http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2008/results/2008_State_General.pdf|publisher=Montana Secretary of State|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115412/http://sos.mt.gov/elections/archives/2000s/2008/results/2008_State_General.pdf|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> He pushed for tougher drunken driving laws and a crackdown on prescription drug abuse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prescription Drug Abuse: What We\u2019re Doing|url=https://doj.mt.gov/prescriptiondrugabuse/what-were-doing/|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731024102/https://doj.mt.gov/prescriptiondrugabuse/what-were-doing/|archive-date=July 31, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He introduced the 24/7 Sobriety Program for repeat DUI offenders statewide.<ref>{{cite web|title=MT Senate Committee passes 24/7 Sobriety Program.|url=http://www.kpax.com/news/mt-senate-committee-passes-24-7-sobriety-program/|publisher=KPAX}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This program requires repeat drunk drivers to take breath tests twice a day. The program is aimed at keeping highways and communities free of drunk drivers, and keeping non-violent offenders out of jail and off the public rolls. The program has had success in dropping DUI offenses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Testing keeps most DUI suspects sober.|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/opinion/editorial/gazette-opinion/gazette-opinion-daily-testing-keeps-most-dui-suspects-sober/article_2dcad937-d778-5192-94fa-2b1699146cd8.html|publisher=The Billings Gazette|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031103627/http://billingsgazette.com/news/opinion/editorial/gazette-opinion/gazette-opinion-daily-testing-keeps-most-dui-suspects-sober/article_2dcad937-d778-5192-94fa-2b1699146cd8.html|archive-date=October 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Attorney General's office also pursued the railroad industry for monopolistic business practices,<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana AG sues Burlington Northern to cover some rail costs|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-ag-sues-burlington-northern-to-cover-some-rail-costs/article_3ac485e8-d389-11de-a252-001cc4c03286.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock: State must protect agricultural producers|url=http://missoulian.com/news/local/bullock-state-must-protect-agriculture-producers/article_8f878094-6cdb-5181-b6b1-106dcab963fb.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119091940/https://missoulian.com/news/local/bullock-state-must-protect-agriculture-producers/article_8f878094-6cdb-5181-b6b1-106dcab963fb.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and led the way in stopping an anti-competitive merger between two the largest meat packers in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana leads 16-state effort to save small farms and ranches|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-leads--state-effort-to-save-small-farms-and/article_132b32fe-3516-11df-b42f-001cc4c03286.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119091913/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/montana-leads--state-effort-to-save-small-farms-and/article_132b32fe-3516-11df-b42f-001cc4c03286.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  Bullock focused on the misclassification of employees as independent contractors and allowing FedEx to avoid paying millions in state taxes and fees. Bullock's efforts resulted in changes by FedEx to comply with federal and state laws.<ref>{{cite web|title=FedEx settles with Montana over classification of delivery drivers|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_077bd806-dcb8-11df-a5d3-001cc4c002e0.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119092029/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_077bd806-dcb8-11df-a5d3-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=November 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock attracted national attention by challenging the ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission|Citizens United]]'' decision through his defense of Montana's 100-year-old ban on corporate campaign expenditures.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Montana\u2014Big Sky, Clean Politics|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/15/opinion/la-oe-bullock-citizens-united-montana-supreme-20120615|work=LA Times|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628112854/http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jun/15/opinion/la-oe-bullock-citizens-united-montana-supreme-20120615|archive-date=June 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> After winning in the Montana Supreme Court, the [[United States Supreme Court|U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled against the State of Montana in a 5-4 decision.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clean and Fair Elections|url=https://doj.mt.gov/campaigns/clean-and-fair-elections/|publisher=Montana Department of Justice|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730235709/https://doj.mt.gov/campaigns/clean-and-fair-elections/|archive-date=July 30, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Court Declines to Revisit its Citizens United Decision|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/26/us/supreme-court-declines-to-revisit-citizens-united.html|work=New York Times|access-date=February 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204124723/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/26/us/supreme-court-declines-to-revisit-citizens-united.html|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock, who authored the state's opinion guaranteeing access to rivers, streams, and public lands, worked with the legislature and Governor Brian Schweitzer to codify the access opinion into law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridge Access Bill Now Law|url=http://www.plwa.org/viewarticle.php?id=106|publisher=Public Land and Water Access Association, Inc|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628134821/http://www.plwa.org/viewarticle.php?id=106|archive-date=June 28, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Montana==\n[[File:Steve Bullock 10-31-2012.jpg|thumb|170px|Bullock at a campaign event in [[Glasgow, Montana]], October 31, 2012.]]\n\n===Elections===\n{{Main|2012 Montana gubernatorial election|2016 Montana gubernatorial election}}\nBullock announced on September 7, 2011, that he would be a candidate for the Democratic nomination for Governor of Montana in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock announces Democratic run for governor via internet, Billings event|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_d0d56966-d991-11e0-81a9-001cc4c002e0.html|publisher=Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203193734/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_d0d56966-d991-11e0-81a9-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=February 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the Democratic primary, Bullock faced off against Helena resident Heather Margolis. Bullock won with 87% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock, Hill win governor primaries|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-hill-win-governor-primaries/article_f1a9c838-b251-514b-8d64-4561b8d179ae.html|publisher=Billings Gazette|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710035623/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-hill-win-governor-primaries/article_f1a9c838-b251-514b-8d64-4561b8d179ae.html|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock and his running mate, then Adjutant General of Montana [[John Walsh (U.S. politician)|John Walsh]], proposed a jobs plan that focuses on small and medium-sized Montana businesses as the engines of job creation. Bullock and General Walsh support:<ref>{{cite web|title=A Jobs Plan for Montana: Part 1: Creating Opportunities for Small Business|url=http://stevebullock.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/BULLOCK-WALSH-JOBS-PLAN-Creating-Opportunites-for-Small-Business.pdf|publisher=stevebullock.com|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517230239/http://stevebullock.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/BULLOCK-WALSH-JOBS-PLAN-Creating-Opportunites-for-Small-Business.pdf|archive-date=May 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Streamlining the regulatory permitting process and establishing a new permit tracking system,\n* Ensuring that government services meet the demands of job creators,\n* Supporting rapid growth in eastern Montana by ensuring that communities receive funds before or in preparation for natural resource development rather than afterwards,\n* Promoting the hiring of Montanans first for jobs inside the state paid for by taxpayers\u2019 money,\n* Expanding in-state business activity to create a business climate that spurs faster expansion and greater business-to-business activity among Montana companies,\n* Further reforming Montana's workers\u2019 compensation system to reduce the number of workers who are injured or killed on the job, getting injured workers back to work as soon as possible and controlling medical costs.\n* Requiring major firms that are awarded state contracts to subcontract a substantial percentage of their work to in-state businesses.\n\nBullock proposed a $400 property tax rebate for homeowners in Montana to spur job creation and refund a portion of the state's $400 million budget surplus.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bullock Proposes $400 tax rebates for Montana homeowners|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-proposes-tax-rebates-for-montana-homeowners/article_42828330-b3f5-11e1-832a-0019bb2963f4.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630221955/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-proposes-tax-rebates-for-montana-homeowners/article_42828330-b3f5-11e1-832a-0019bb2963f4.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJohn Walsh, Bullock's running mate, is the former Adjutant General of the Montana National Guard.<ref>{{cite web|title=Democrat Bullock taps former Montana adjutant general for lieutenant governor|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_f2655054-6998-11e1-8e46-001871e3ce6c.html|publisher=The Missoulian|access-date=August 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819234316/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/article_f2655054-6998-11e1-8e46-001871e3ce6c.html|archive-date=August 19, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock won the election, held on November 6, 2012, defeating Republican ex-US Representative Rick Hill.<ref>[http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/networks-declare-bullock-winner-in-tight-race-for-governor/article_6e665ae8-252f-11e2-b495-001a4bcf887a.html Networks Declare Bullock Winner in Tight Race for Governor] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110070148/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/networks-declare-bullock-winner-in-tight-race-for-governor/article_6e665ae8-252f-11e2-b495-001a4bcf887a.html |date=November 10, 2012 }}, ''The Billings Gazette'' by Charles S. Johnson. November 6, 2012. Retrieved November 7, 2012.</ref>  Bullock came out on top by 7,571 votes, or 48.9%, to Hill's 47.3%.  Libertarian candidate Ron Vandevender pulled 3.8% of the vote.<ref>Michael Barone, et al. ''The Almanac of American Politics 2014'' (2013) (Kindle Locations 48242-48245).</ref>\n\n===First term===\nGovernor Bullock and his lieutenant governor, John Walsh, were sworn in on January 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/local/bullock-invites-residents-to-inauguration-ceremony/article_b158f6d6-b734-5878-9018-a18a6251ab9a.html|title=Bullock invites residents to inauguration ceremony|work=Billings Gazette|accessdate=May 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110946/http://billingsgazette.com/news/local/bullock-invites-residents-to-inauguration-ceremony/article_b158f6d6-b734-5878-9018-a18a6251ab9a.html|archive-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock later appointed Walsh to become the new [[United States Senate|Senator]] from Montana to replace [[Max Baucus]], who had been appointed [[United States Ambassador to China|Ambassador to China]].  Bullock then appointed [[Angela McLean]] to replace Walsh as lieutenant governor.\n\nIn November 2015, McLean announced her resignation as lieutenant governor, effective upon the appointment of her successor, in order to accept the position of director of American Indian and minority achievement in the office of the state commissioner of higher education.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dennison |first=Mike |date=November 30, 2015 |title=Lt. Gov. McLean resigning to take higher-ed job |url=http://www.krtv.com/story/30630748/lt-gov-mclean-resigns-to-take-higher-ed-job |newspaper=KRTV-TV |location=Great Falls, MT |access-date=May 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043928/http://www.krtv.com/story/30630748/lt-gov-mclean-resigns-to-take-higher-ed-job |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Bullock announced the appointment of [[Mike Cooney]] as McLean's replacement. Cooney was sworn in on January 4, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://helenair.com/news/politics/mike-cooney-chosen-as-montana-s-next-lieutenant-governor/article_1d3bf1d1-2736-53e0-b6a2-d096a3d01ca6.html|title=Mike Cooney chosen as Montana's next lieutenant governor|author=Holly Michels|work=Helena Independent Record|accessdate=February 15, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303024055/http://helenair.com/news/politics/mike-cooney-chosen-as-montana-s-next-lieutenant-governor/article_1d3bf1d1-2736-53e0-b6a2-d096a3d01ca6.html|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a September 20, 2016, survey by ''[[Morning Consult]]'', Bullock, with a 66% approval rating and a 19% disapproval rating, was the most popular Democratic governor in the United States, as well as the fourth-most popular overall, behind Republicans [[Dennis Daugaard]] of [[Governor of South Dakota|South Dakota]], [[Larry Hogan]] of [[Governor of Maryland|Maryland]], and [[Charlie Baker]] of [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Carter|first=Troy|url=http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/blogs/politics/morning-consult-bullock-approval-rating-at-percent/article_84013542-ed0a-5276-9650-912e3738bc56.html|title=Morning Consult: Bullock approval rating at 66 percent|work=[[Bozeman Daily Chronicle]]|date=September 20, 2016|accessdate=March 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617022324/http://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/blogs/politics/morning-consult-bullock-approval-rating-at-percent/article_84013542-ed0a-5276-9650-912e3738bc56.html|archive-date=June 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\nBullock began his second term on January 2, 2017, alongside [[List of lieutenant governors of Montana|Montana Lieutenant Governor]] [[Mike Cooney]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Steve Bullock Sworn in as Montana\u2019s 24th Governor |url=http://governor.mt.gov/Newsroom/governor-steve-bullock-sworn-in-as-montanas-24th-governor |publisher=Office of Governor Steve Bullock |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904225832/http://governor.mt.gov/Newsroom/governor-steve-bullock-sworn-in-as-montanas-24th-governor |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock and Cooney were the only two Democrats to retain statewide offices in the 2016 elections as the Republicans captured the offices of [[Montana Office of Public Instruction|Montana Superintendent of Public Instruction]], [[Montana State Auditor]], and [[Montana Secretary of State]] and held onto the offices of [[Montana Attorney General]] and U.S. Representative for [[Montana's at-large congressional district]].<ref name=\"Bozeman Daily Chronicle\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Working together civilly is opening-day theme at Capitol |url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/mtleg/working-together-civilly-is-opening-day-theme-at-capitol/article_6665f579-595c-5aba-a286-ff858124449d.html |website=Bozeman Daily Chronicle |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Following the 2016 elections, Bullock faced large Republican majorities in the [[Montana Legislature]]. The Republicans gained three State Senate seats and widened their Senate majority over the Democrats to 32-18 while maintaining a 59-41 majority in the [[Montana House of Representatives]], the same as in 2015.<ref name=\"Bozeman Daily Chronicle\"/>\n\nIn the 2018 state legislative elections in Montana, Democrats won 42 of 100 seats in the [[Montana House of Representatives]] and gained two seats in the [[Montana Senate]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Montana Election Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-montana-elections.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> This meant that, in the 2019 state legislative session that Bullock presided over, Republicans held 60 percent of the seats in the upper chamber and 58 percent of the seats in the lower chamber of the [[Montana Legislature]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Drake |first1=Phil |title=Sine die: 66th legislative session is over |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2019/04/25/montana-legislature-adjourns/3577013002/ |website=Great Falls Tribune |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n[[File:Steve Bullock (48537192076).jpg|right|thumb|Bullock speaking at the 2019 Des Moines Register Soapbox at the Iowa State Fair.]]\n[[File:Steve Bullock 2020 presidential campaign logo.svg|thumb|right|200px|Bullock's 2020 presidential campaign logo]]\nIn 2017 Bullock formed the Big Sky Values PAC, which by spring 2019 had raised nearly $1.8 million, to pay for travel around the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=Montana governor Steve Bullock to announce bid for presidency: report|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/441623-montana-governor-steve-bullock-to-announce-bid-for-presidency-report|access-date=May 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502231144/https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/441623-montana-governor-steve-bullock-to-announce-bid-for-presidency-report|archive-date=May 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On May 14, 2019, Bullock announced his candidacy for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/steve-bullock-2020-montana-governor-running-for-president-watch-video-announcement-today-05-14-2019/|title=Steve Bullock, Montana governor, announces he's running for president|author=Camilo Montoya-Galvez|date=May 14, 2019|work=[[CBS]]|accessdate=May 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514192140/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/steve-bullock-2020-montana-governor-running-for-president-watch-video-announcement-today-05-14-2019/|archive-date=May 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In his announcement video, Bullock said that opposing political \"[[dark money]]\" and legislating against the ''[[Citizens United v. FEC|Citizens United]]'' Supreme Court ruling would be among his utmost priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Raymond |last=Arke |authorlink   =|title= Opposed to \u2018dark money\u2019 and Citizens United, Montana Gov. Steve Bullock enters 2020 Democratic primary  |publisher=[[OpenSecrets.org]]|date=May 14, 2019 |url= https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2019/05/opposed-to-dark-money-and-citizens-united-montana-gov-steve-bullock-enters-2020-democratic-primary/ |accessdate=}}</ref> Based on his three statewide electoral victories in a largely rural state, Bullock held a certain cachet of \"electability\", and appeared to have a plausible path to the nomination.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/how-steve-bullock-could-win-the-2020-democratic-primary/ |title=How Steve Bullock Could Win The 2020 Democratic Primary |author=Rakich, Nathaniel |authorlink= |date=May 14, 2019 |publisher= |website=[[Fivethirtyeight.com]] |accessdate=December 4, 2019 |archiveurl= |archivedate= |url-status= }}</ref> His mid-May entrance was relatively late, but he was still able to qualify for the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|second Democratic debate]] in July.<ref name=\"EpsteinStevens\">{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/02/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020-drops-out.html |title=Steve Bullock Drops Out of 2020 Presidential Race |author1=Epstein, Reid J. |author2=Stevens, Matt |date=December 2, 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |url-status= }}</ref> Even so, the late start left him with less media exposure than his numerous rivals: he found it hard to raise funds, and never rose above 1% in nationwide polls.<ref name=\"EpsteinStevens\"/> He ended his campaign on December 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weigel |first1=David |title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock drops out of presidential race |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-drops-out-of-presidential-race/2019/12/01/26c220ec-14a0-11ea-a659-7d69641c6ff7_story.html|website=Washington Post |accessdate=December 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==2020 Senate campaign==\n{{Main|2020 United States Senate election in Montana}}\nOn March 4, 2020, after months of speculation and denials from Bullock himself, the New York Times reported that Bullock would file in Montana's U.S. Senate [[2020 United States Senate election in Montana|election]] to challenge Republican incumbent [[Steve Daines]]. The move came after Senate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] (D-NY) personally flew to Montana to convince Bullock to run, and after Bullock talked with former president [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Steve Bullock Is Running for Senate in Montana|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/us/politics/steve-bullock-montana-senate.html|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> Both believed that he was the only formidable candidate against Daines.<ref>{{cite news|title= Schumer meets with Bullock as Montana filing deadline for Senate seat nears|url= https://www.politico.com/amp/news/2020/02/25/schumer-meets-bullock-montana-senate-seat-117479|last=Everett|first=Burgess|publisher=Politico|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2020}} Bullock is running for the seat formerly held for six terms by Democrat Max Baucus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-09/senior-adviser-montana-gov-steve-bullock-to-run-for-senate|title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock to run for Senate|date=2020-03-09|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> \n\nSteve Bullock officially declared his candidacy on March 9, 2020, which was the last day to file.<ref>https://twitter.com/stevebullockmt/status/1236986586606100481</ref> The announcement prompted all other candidates who were already running for the Democratic nomination except one to drop out and endorse Bullock. This included the mayor of Helena, [[Wilmot Collins]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Wilmot |title=Thank you, Montana. It's been my honor to run for U.S. Senate. Today I\u2019m suspending my campaign and endorsing Governor Steve Bullock. |url=https://twitter.com/CollinsWilmot/status/1237147675054600192 |website=@CollinsWilmot |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Neumann|first=Cora|title=Cora Neumann withdraws from Montana senate race, endorses Steve Bullock|url= https://mobile.twitter.com/CoraforMT/status/1237028772018180097|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref> https://mobile.twitter.com/KnolesMichael/status/1236997949730611207</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stein |first1=Perrin |title=Bozeman Senate candidate drops out of race, supports Bullock |url=https://www.bozemandailychronicle.com/news/politics/bozeman-senate-candidate-drops-out-of-race-supports-bullock/article_548ab9a5-c981-50c1-a3b4-044e0ec54df2.html |website=Bozeman Daily Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\nBullock has been described by ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and ''[[ABC News]]'' as a [[moderate Democrat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-considering-2020-white-house-bid-now-says-he-supports-assault-weapons-ban/2018/08/19/58f4a34c-a3f8-11e8-a656-943eefab5daf_story.html|title=Montana Gov. Steve Bullock, considering 2020 White House bid, says he supports assault weapons ban|last=Sonmez|first=Felicia|date=August 19, 2018|website=washingtonpost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207091850/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/montana-gov-steve-bullock-considering-2020-white-house-bid-now-says-he-supports-assault-weapons-ban/2018/08/19/58f4a34c-a3f8-11e8-a656-943eefab5daf_story.html|archive-date=December 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/red-state-governor-democrats-lose-midterms-referendum-donald/story?id=57477278|title=Democratic governor of Montana says 'no secret recipe' as he eyes 2020|date=August 29, 2018|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=December 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124148/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/red-state-governor-democrats-lose-midterms-referendum-donald/story?id=57477278|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to Bullock as being among [[Centrism|centrist]] Democratic governors.<ref name=NYTimes17July2017>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/17/us/politics/democrat-governors-bullock-mcauliffe.html|title=As Party Drifts Left, Pragmatic Democratic Governors Have Eye on White House|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=July 17, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 8, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129073634/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/17/us/politics/democrat-governors-bullock-mcauliffe.html|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The non-partisan organization, [[On the Issues|On The Issues]], which tracks candidates' positions and records, considers Bullock to be a \"Moderate Liberal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Steve_Bullock.htm|title=Steve Bullock on the Issues|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107202331/http://www.ontheissues.org/Steve_Bullock.htm|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nBullock is pro-choice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Decides? The Status Of Women's Reproductive Rights in the United States|date=February 6, 2018|url=https://www.prochoiceamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/WhoDecides2018-withCover-1.pdf|website=NARAL|publisher=NARAL: Pro-Choice America|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427045435/https://www.prochoiceamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/WhoDecides2018-withCover-1.pdf|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During the 2017 state legislative session, Bullock vetoed two bills (SB 282, SB 329) aimed at restricting late-term abortions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flatheadbeacon.com/2017/05/02/passed-failed-montana-legislature/|title=What Passed and What Failed at the Montana Legislature|last=Scott|first=Tristan|date=May 2, 2017|work=Flathead Beacon|access-date=January 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115075828/https://flatheadbeacon.com/2017/05/02/passed-failed-montana-legislature/|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Governor Bullock Stands With Montana Families By Vetoing Extreme Bills Endangering Women|url=https://www.aclumontana.org/en/press-releases/governor-bullock-stands-montana-families-vetoing-extreme-bills-endangering-women|website=American Civil Liberties Union of Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702093732/https://www.aclumontana.org/en/press-releases/governor-bullock-stands-montana-families-vetoing-extreme-bills-endangering-women|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock received a 100 percent rating from [[NARAL]] in 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Steve Bullock's Ratings and Endorsements|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/110899/steve-bullock#.Wzm38NhKjOQ|website=Vote Smart: Facts Matter|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702093326/https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/110899/steve-bullock#.Wzm38NhKjOQ|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was endorsed by [[Planned Parenthood]] Advocates of Montana in his successful 2016 reelection bid.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stahl|first1=Martha|title=Big Sky Impact: Election Recap|url=https://www.plannedparenthood.org/uploads/filer_public/dd/3c/dd3c6ace-071c-4b50-9bae-cde793dfea69/pp_winternews2016-17_web.pdf|website=Planned Parenthood Advocates of Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516235247/https://www.plannedparenthood.org/uploads/filer_public/dd/3c/dd3c6ace-071c-4b50-9bae-cde793dfea69/pp_winternews2016-17_web.pdf|archive-date=May 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was one of 14 Democratic governors to write a letter to [[Alex Azar]], President Trump's [[Secretary of Health and Human Services]], on March 31, 2018 demanding that Title X funding for women's reproductive health care and family planning remain in effect. The 14 governors threatened legal action if the Trump administration were to undermine women's access to reproductive health care.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Inslee|first1=Jay|title=Letter to Alex Azar|url=https://democraticgovernors.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/DGA-Letter-Title-X.pdf|website=Democratic Governors Association|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215212821/https://democraticgovernors.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/DGA-Letter-Title-X.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Campaign finance reform===\nAs Attorney General of Montana, Bullock advocated on behalf of the state's century-old ban on corporate money in elections, the [[Montana Corrupt Practices Act of 1912]]. After that and similar laws were struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court's ''[[Citizens United]]'' decision in 2010, Bullock countered with a new case, ''American Tradition Partnership, Inc. v. Bullock'' (2012). Although the Supreme Court disposed of the case in a 5-4 decision,<ref>{{cite web |title=AMERICAN TRADITION PARTNERSHIP, INC. v. BULLOCK |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/11-1179 |website=Legal Information Institute |publisher=Cornell Law School |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192224/https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/11-1179 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bullock continued to advocate for campaign finance reform throughout his time as Governor of Montana.<ref name=\"Billings Gazette\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Bullock signs Montana campaign finance bill into law |url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/bullock-signs-montana-campaign-finance-bill-into-law/article_c8a0cc59-a7bf-5381-9136-ae118d9a13ff.html |website=Billings Gazette |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904191908/https://billingsgazette.com/news/government-and-politics/bullock-signs-montana-campaign-finance-bill-into-law/article_c8a0cc59-a7bf-5381-9136-ae118d9a13ff.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Memoli |first1=Mike |title=Montana governor pushes for more transparency on donors |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/card/montana-governor-pushes-more-transparency-donors-n880316 |website=NBC News |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905052524/https://www.nbcnews.com/card/montana-governor-pushes-more-transparency-donors-n880316 |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bullock steered the DISCLOSE Act, a bipartisan campaign finance reform bill that bolstered disclosure requirements in Montana elections, through a GOP-controlled state legislature.<ref name=\"Billings Gazette\"/><ref>{{Cite AV media |people=Soboroff, Jacob |title=MSNBC's American Swamp: Governor Bullock leading the fight against dark money in politics |medium=Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uyL2h8e0CNI |publisher=Steve Bullock <!-- Official YouTube account --> |location= |date=July 29, 2019 |time= }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Bullock signed an executive order that required the recipients of major government contracts in Montana to disclose \"[[dark money]] spending\" in elections, including spending disclosure that is not explicitly required by federal law.<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=Bullock tells Montana contractors to report \u2018dark money\u2019 |url=https://coloradopolitics.com/out-west-roundup-bullock-tells-montana-contractors-report-dark-money/ |website=CP: Colorado Politics |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192022/https://coloradopolitics.com/out-west-roundup-bullock-tells-montana-contractors-report-dark-money/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2018, Bullock sued the Internal Revenue Service and the U.S. Department of the Treasury<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanson |first1=Amy Beth |title=Montana governor sues over IRS policy on tax-exempt groups |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/montana-governor-sues-over-irs-policy-on-tax-exempt-groups/ |website=Seattle Times |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192246/https://www.seattletimes.com/business/montana-governor-sues-over-irs-policy-on-tax-exempt-groups/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> over a recent decision to dispense with donor requirements for nonprofit organizations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lorenzo |first1=Aaron |title=Treasury defends move to halt nonprofit disclosures amid Wyden threat |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/17/treasury-nonprofit-donor-disclosures-690200 |website=Politico |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903140946/https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/17/treasury-nonprofit-donor-disclosures-690200 |archive-date=September 3, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Climate change and environment===\nBullock believes that climate change is real and that humans contribute to it,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hegyi |first1=Nate |title=Montana Governor Says Ignoring Climate Change Is 'Shortsighted And Dangerous' |url=https://www.mtpr.org/post/montana-governor-says-ignoring-climate-change-shortsighted-and-dangerous |website=Montana Public Radio |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514170114/https://www.mtpr.org/post/montana-governor-says-ignoring-climate-change-shortsighted-and-dangerous |archive-date=May 14, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last1=Harball |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Beck |first2=Madelyn |title=Obama climate rule looms large in Mont. governor's race |url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060033730 |website=E&E News |accessdate=April 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515141541/http://www.eenews.net/stories/1060033730 |archive-date=May 15, 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> but Montana became the first state to halt preparations for the [[Clean Power Plan]] when the [[United States Supreme Court]] announced a stay of the plan in February 2016.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIn September 2014, Bullock signed an executive order creating a habitat conservation plan for [[Centrocercus|sage-grouse]] in a bid to keep management of the imperiled bird in state hands rather than see it come under federal Endangered Species Act protection. The government said to the press: \"Montanans recognize that it is in the best interest of our state, its economy and our quality of life to maintain state management of the greater sage-grouse.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zuckermann|first1=Laura|title=Montana governor issues sage grouse conservation plan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/10/us-usa-sagegrouse-montana-idUSKBN0H502420140910|accessdate=September 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913094616/http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/10/us-usa-sagegrouse-montana-idUSKBN0H502420140910|archive-date=September 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2019, Bullock was the only remaining 2020 Democratic presidential candidate who had not yet signed the No Fossil Fuel Money pledge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nofossilfuelmoney.org/presidential-signers/|title=Pledge Signers - Presidential|work=No Fossil Fuel Money Pledge|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic Party===\nBullock endorsed [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 general election]], but expressed disagreement with Clinton's opposition to coal mining because it is an important industry in Montana. He did not attend the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]], citing his duties as [[Governor of Montana]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Retana|first1=Judith|title=Bullock will not attend DNC, still endorses Clinton|url=http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/bullock-will-not-attend-dnc-still-endorses-clinton|website=NBC Montana|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703021825/http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/bullock-will-not-attend-dnc-still-endorses-clinton|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Bullock appears to have stayed neutral during the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hillary Endorsements - The 5 GOVs She Needs For a Sweep (OT Update: Donna Edwards has endorsed HRC)|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/17/1450543/-Hillary-Endorsements-The-5-GOVs-She-Needs-For-a-Sweep|website=Daily Kos|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702204814/https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/17/1450543/-Hillary-Endorsements-The-5-GOVs-She-Needs-For-a-Sweep|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was chairman of the [[Democratic Governors Association]] in 2015, overseeing the [[2015 Louisiana gubernatorial election|election]] of Gov. [[John Bel Edwards]] of [[Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=DGA Chair Governor Steve Bullock's Statement on Louisiana Victory|url=https://democraticgovernors.org/news/dga-chair-governor-steve-bullocks-statement-on-louisiana-victory|website=Democratic Governors Association|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090004/https://democraticgovernors.org/news/dga-chair-governor-steve-bullocks-statement-on-louisiana-victory/|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> a pro-life [[Southern Democrat]] who expanded Medicaid to more than 471,000 Louisianans and reformed his state's criminal justice system  after winning the [[Governor of Louisiana|governorship]] of a heavily Republican state.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Crisp|first1=Elizabeth|title=Poll: Louisiana residents view Medicaid expansion, criminal justice changes favorably|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/politics/legislature/article_08d336ca-3f45-11e8-bb7f-fb5c1c1a0b96.html|website=The Advocate (Baton Rouge, LA)|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702233147/https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/politics/legislature/article_08d336ca-3f45-11e8-bb7f-fb5c1c1a0b96.html|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Bullock expressed that there are \"roles for all of us [Democrats]\" within the party, referring to liberal, moderate, and conservative Democrats alike.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cheney|first1=Kyle|last2=Pradhan|first2=Rachana|title=Red-state Democrats fret about leftward shift|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/red-state-democrats-leftward-shift-120605|website=Politico: Elections|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703021817/https://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/red-state-democrats-leftward-shift-120605|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBullock was one of just three Democrats to win gubernatorial elections in 2016 in states that President Trump carried that year (one of whom, [[Jim Justice]], is now a Republican), and the only incumbent Democratic governor to win re-election in a state that Trump carried.<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=2016 Governor Election Results |url=https://www.politico.com/mapdata-2016/2016-election/results/map/governor/ |website=Politico |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064031/https://www.politico.com/mapdata-2016/2016-election/results/map/governor/ |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was also one of the few Democratic incumbents besides [[North Carolina State Auditor]] [[Beth Wood]],<ref>{{cite web |title=North Carolina Auditor Results: Beth Wood Leads |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina-auditor |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064122/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina-auditor |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[North Carolina Secretary of State]] [[Elaine Marshall]],<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=North Carolina Results |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina |website=The New York Times |access-date=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705210333/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina |archive-date=July 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> West Virginia State Treasurer [[John Perdue]],<ref>{{cite web |title=West Virginia Treasurer Results: John Perdue Wins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/west-virginia-treasurer |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034646/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/west-virginia-treasurer |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and [[Pennsylvania Auditor General]] [[Eugene DePasquale]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania Auditor General Results: Eugene DePasquale Wins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/pennsylvania-auditor-general |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723034637/https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/pennsylvania-auditor-general |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> to win re-election to statewide offices in states that President Trump won in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].\n\nSince the [[2016 United States elections|2016 elections]], in which Democrats lost the [[2016 United States presidential election|presidency]], ceded control of several [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2016|governorships]], and came short of winning majorities in the [[2016 United States Senate elections|U.S. Senate]] and [[2016 United States House of Representatives elections|U.S. House of Representatives]], Bullock has publicly argued that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] needs to expand its reach beyond urban areas and the nation's two coasts. He has encouraged Democrats to engage with and attempt to persuade voters in suburban and rural areas rather than relying solely on base turnout.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=May 16, 2017 CAP Ideas Conference: Gov. Steve Bullock (D-MT)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iu73mHdRrYk|website=Center for American Progress|publisher=Center for American Progress|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090100/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iu73mHdRrYk|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bullock|first1=Steve|title=How Democrats Can Win in the West|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/opinion/steve-bullock-democrats-montana.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702211936/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/opinion/steve-bullock-democrats-montana.html|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He  visited Iowa,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Volz|first1=Matt|title=Gov. Bullock travels to Iowa as he explores possible 2020 run for president|url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/04/06/montana-governor-travels-iowa-he-explores-possible-presidential-run-steve-bullock/495026002|website=Great Falls Tribune|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Wisconsin,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Charles|title=Possible 2020 presidential candidate Steve Bullock visits Milwaukee|url=https://www.tmj4.com/news/local-news/possible-2020-presidential-candidate-steve-bullock-visits-milwaukee|website=Today's TMJ-4: WTMJ-TV Milwaukee|publisher=Scripps TV Station Group|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627033943/https://www.tmj4.com/news/local-news/possible-2020-presidential-candidate-steve-bullock-visits-milwaukee|archive-date=June 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and Colorado<ref>{{cite web|last1=Luning|first1=Ernest|title=Montana Governor Steve Bullock tapped to keynote Colorado Democrats\u2019 annual dinner|url=https://coloradopolitics.com/montana-governor-steve-bullock-tapped-keynote-colorado-democrats-annual-dinner|website=Colorado Politics|publisher=Colorado Politics|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702204551/https://coloradopolitics.com/montana-governor-steve-bullock-tapped-keynote-colorado-democrats-annual-dinner/|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> to campaign for and speak in support of Democratic candidates during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 election cycle]], which saw Democrats retake the majority in the U.S. House and gain governorships and state legislature seats. Bullock's visits around the country led some to speculate that he was considering a run for [[President of the United States]], which turned out to be true when he announced his candidacy for president on May 14, 2019.<ref>State of the Union, Jake Tapper, CNN August 19, 2018</ref>\n\n===Death penalty===\nIn 2019, Bullock said he supports the [[death penalty]] in \u201climited circumstances\u201d like terrorism \u2014 a stance that distinguished the former state attorney general from the crowded 2020 Democratic presidential field.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/jun/19/steve-bullock-supports-death-penalty-limited-circu/|title=Steve Bullock supports death penalty in \u2018limited\u2019 circumstances|work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\nUntil at least 2016, Bullock opposed [[gun control]] and [[universal background checks]] and stated that as governor \"our [[Second Amendment]] rights have been expanded in Montana.\u201d<ref name=NYTimes14May2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/14/us/politics/steve-bullock-on-the-issues.html?searchResultPosition=2 |title=Where Steve Bullock Stands on the Issues|last=Astor|first=Maggie|date=May 14, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 31, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2018, he changed his positions to support [[universal background checks]], limits on [[High-capacity magazine|magazine sizes]], temporary removal of firearms from potentially violent people ([[red flag laws]]), and  banning certain types of [[Semi-automatic firearm|\"semiautomatic weapons\"]].<ref name=NYTimes14May2019/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nBullock expanded [[Medicaid]] coverage in Montana under the [[Affordable Care Act]] with a Republican-dominated state legislature. He is in favor of expanding accessibility to healthcare and trying to protect, improve, and strengthen the Affordable Care Act and does not favor a [[single-payer system]].<ref name=NYTimes17July2017/><ref name=NYTimes14May2019/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020-campaign.html?searchResultPosition=6#health |title=Meet the Candidates: 18 Questions. 21 Democrats. Here\u2019s What They Said.|date=2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 31, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nThen-Attorney General Steve Bullock opposed a 2012 voter-approved law in the State of Montana, Legislative Referendum 121, that would have required state agencies to verify through a federal database whether individuals requesting certain services were U.S. citizens.<ref name=\"USA Todat\">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=John S. |title=Court strikes down Montana immigration law |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/23/court-strikes-montana-immigration-law/11276379/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904231232/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/23/court-strikes-montana-immigration-law/11276379/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The law, which had been intended to deny government jobs and assistance to undocumented immigrants, was ruled unconstitutional and legally unenforceable.<ref name=\"USA Todat\"/>\n\nDespite pushback from Republican state legislators, Governor Bullock supported allowing Syrian refugees to resettle in the State of Montana in 2015, but promised that ensuring the safety of Montanans would be his \"top priority\" during the resettlement process.<ref name=\"Missoulian\">{{cite web |last1=Michels |first1=Holly |title=[UPDATED] 55 legislators tell Bullock to block Syrian refugees |url=https://missoulian.com/helena/news/politics/state/updated-legislators-tell-bullock-to-block-syrian-refugees/article_0dcdcbd2-1e97-596b-be7c-2bac2478003a.html |website=Missoulian |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192159/https://missoulian.com/helena/news/politics/state/updated-legislators-tell-bullock-to-block-syrian-refugees/article_0dcdcbd2-1e97-596b-be7c-2bac2478003a.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> At least 31 other governors at the time opposed the resettlement of Syrian refugees.<ref name=\"Missoulian\"/>\n\nBullock supports the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program and signed a letter on September 7, 2017, alongside 10 other governors to congressional leaders in support of legislation that would protect DACA recipients and \"take immediate action to ensure that these young people can continue to live, work, and contribute to the country they have called home for most of their lives.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Tara |title=11 governors urge Congress to take immediate action to protect DACA recipients |url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/11-governors-urge-congress-take-immediate-action-protect-daca-recipients |website=Washington Governor Jay Inslee |publisher=State of Washington |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904193136/https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/11-governors-urge-congress-take-immediate-action-protect-daca-recipients |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 2018, Bullock refused to deploy National Guard troops from Montana to the Mexican border \"based simply on the whim of the President's morning Twitter habit\".<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |title=Bullock says no to Guard deployment based on Trump's 'whim' |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/04/05/bullock-says-no-guard-deployment-based-trumps-whim/491796002/ |website=Great Falls Tribune |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Bullock voiced strong opposition to the Trump administration's policy of family separations at the Mexican border, and said in a statement: \"As a governor and a father, I'm disgusted. I don't care if it's the President or Congress \u2013 these atrocities must end immediately.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Inslee |first1=Jay (Chair) |title=VIDEO: Dem Govs Lead Pushback to Trump on Child Separation Crisis |url=https://democraticgovernors.org/news/video-dem-govs-lead-pushback-to-trump-on-child-separation-crisis/ |website=Democratic Governors Association |publisher=Democratic Governors Association |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427090107/https://democraticgovernors.org/news/video-dem-govs-lead-pushback-to-trump-on-child-separation-crisis/ |archive-date=April 27, 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage===\nBullock supports [[same-sex marriage]], and praised the federal judge who struck down Montana's same-sex marriage ban in 2014, making Montana the 34th U.S. state to legalize same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Whitcomb |first1=Dan |title=U.S. judge strikes down Montana's gay marriage ban |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-gaymarriage-montana-idUSKCN0J32FL20141119 |website=Reuters: U.S. |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719061628/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-gaymarriage-montana-idUSKCN0J32FL20141119 |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He also supported the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', which legalized same-sex marriage nationwide, and said in a statement on June 26, 2015: \u201cThis ruling protects the right of all Montanans to marry the person they love, and moves our state and nation closer to the promise of freedom, dignity, and equality that they were founded upon. All people, regardless of their sexual orientation, should have the opportunity to make a good life for themselves and their families.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Dave |title=BULLOCK STATEMENT ON MARRIAGE EQUALITY RULING |url=https://news.mt.gov/bullock-statement-on-marriage-equality-ruling |website=Montana.Gov: Official State Website |publisher=State of Montana |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054238/https://news.mt.gov/bullock-statement-on-marriage-equality-ruling |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock has also spoken at Pride rallies in Montana,<ref>{{cite web |title=Acceptance and equality focus of Big Sky Pride Rally |url=http://www.kxlh.com/story/32254139/acceptance-and-equality-focus-of-big-sky-pride-rally |website=9KXLH.com: Montana's News Leader, Helena and Central Montana |publisher=Cordillera Communications |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054536/http://www.kxlh.com/story/32254139/acceptance-and-equality-focus-of-big-sky-pride-rally |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kuglin |first1=Tom |title='Show them our hearts': Big Sky Pride marks 25th year with parade and rally in Helena |url=https://helenair.com/news/local/show-them-our-hearts-big-sky-pride-marks-th-year/article_63b80587-a843-5288-8908-3ec8c973542f.html |website=Helena Independent Record |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719083733/https://helenair.com/news/local/show-them-our-hearts-big-sky-pride-marks-th-year/article_63b80587-a843-5288-8908-3ec8c973542f.html |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and, in 2015, became the first sitting governor in Montana history to officiate a same-sex wedding.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Drake |first1=Phil |title=Bullock first Montana governor to officiate same-sex wedding |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2015/10/23/bullock-1st-montana-gov-officiate-same-sex-wedding/74456124/|website=Great Falls Tribune |accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Bullock enacted an executive order that prohibits state agencies, state contractors, and subcontractors, from  discriminating in employment on the basis of sexual orientation or [[gender identity]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dehaven |first1=James |title=Bullock expands discrimination ban to cover gender identity, military service, pregnancy |url=https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-expands-discrimination-ban-to-cover-gender-identity-military-service/article_ab153e85-762f-58ce-a7ba-d556ac49f564.html |website=Missoulian |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719054753/https://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/bullock-expands-discrimination-ban-to-cover-gender-identity-military-service/article_ab153e85-762f-58ce-a7ba-d556ac49f564.html |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The executive order expanded upon a previous one signed by former Governor [[Brian Schweitzer]] in 2008, which had similar goals but did not include protections for gender identity and did not apply to contractors or subcontractors.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Metzger |first1=Ianthe |title=Montana Gov Steve Bullock Signs Executive Order Protecting LGBT State Employees |url=https://www.hrc.org/blog/montana-governor-steve-bullock-signs-executive-order-protecting-lgbt-state |website=Human Rights Campaign |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715104920/http://www.hrc.org/blog/montana-governor-steve-bullock-signs-executive-order-protecting-lgbt-state |archive-date=July 15, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Net neutrality===\nBullock supports [[net neutrality]] and opposed the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s decision to repeal net neutrality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lecher |first1=Colin |title=Montana governor signs executive order to keep net neutrality in the state |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16920192/montana-governor-net-neutrality-executive-order |website=The Verge |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905141049/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16920192/montana-governor-net-neutrality-executive-order |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> On January 22, 2018, Bullock signed an executive order prohibiting any internet service provider with a state government contract from blocking or charging additional fees for faster delivery of websites, two major principles of net neutrality.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kang |first1=Cecelia |title=Montana Governor Signs Order to Force Net Neutrality |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/22/technology/montana-net-neutrality.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904205107/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/22/technology/montana-net-neutrality.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Through this executive order, Montana became the first state to implement and enforce net neutrality after the FCC repeal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neidig |first1=Harper |title=Montana becomes first state to implement net neutrality after FCC repeal |url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/370133-montana-becomes-first-state-to-implement-net-neutrality-rules-following-fcc |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102120/http://thehill.com/policy/technology/370133-montana-becomes-first-state-to-implement-net-neutrality-rules-following-fcc |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The governors of [[New York (state)|New York]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Governor Cuomo Signs Executive Order to Protect and Strengthen Net Neutrality in New York |url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-signs-executive-order-protect-and-strengthen-net-neutrality-new-york |website=Office of Governor Andrew M. Cuomo |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102201/https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-signs-executive-order-protect-and-strengthen-net-neutrality-new-york |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Neidig |first1=Harper |title=New Jersey governor signs net neutrality order |url=http://thehill.com/policy/technology/372409-new-jersey-governor-signs-net-neutrality-order |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corporation |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102107/http://thehill.com/policy/technology/372409-new-jersey-governor-signs-net-neutrality-order |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Vermont]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Kieren |title=Vermont becomes fifth US state to boot up its own net neutrality rules |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/02/16/vermont_net_neutrality_rules/ |website=The Register |publisher=Situation Publishing |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905175614/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2018/02/16/vermont_net_neutrality_rules/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Hawaii]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leong |first1=Jodi |last2=McMillan |first2=Cindy |title=GOVERNOR IGE SIGNS EXECUTIVE ORDER TO PROTECT NET NEUTRALITY IN HAWAI\u2018I |url=https://governor.hawaii.gov/newsroom/latest-news/governor-ige-signs-executive-order-to-protect-net-neutrality-in-hawaii/ |website=State of Hawaii |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905102151/https://governor.hawaii.gov/newsroom/latest-news/governor-ige-signs-executive-order-to-protect-net-neutrality-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and [[Rhode Island]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Patrick |title=Raimondo orders state agencies to use internet providers that observe net neutrality |url=http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180424/raimondo-orders-state-agencies-to-use-internet-providers-that-observe-net-neutrality |website=Providence Journal|accessdate=September 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905142605/http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180424/raimondo-orders-state-agencies-to-use-internet-providers-that-observe-net-neutrality |archive-date=September 5, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> eventually followed suit.\n\n===Organized labor===\nBullock has been recognized and endorsed by the [[American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (AFL-CIO),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calvan |first1=Bobby Caina |title=AFL-CIO leader vows union support for Bullock, Juneau |url=https://www.apnews.com/bd61c5b2e69a4b4897db06523f0b161f |website=Associated Press |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192042/https://www.apnews.com/bd61c5b2e69a4b4897db06523f0b161f |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and by the Montana Education Association - Montana Federation of Teachers,<ref>{{cite web |last1=P\u00e9rez |first1=F\u00e9lix |title=Governors races in MO, MT and NC put spotlight on students, educators |url=https://educationvotes.nea.org/2016/08/26/governors-races-mo-mt-nc-put-spotlight-students-educators/ |website=Education Votes |publisher=National Education Association |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904191958/https://educationvotes.nea.org/2016/08/26/governors-races-mo-mt-nc-put-spotlight-students-educators/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> for his support of worker's rights and public education.\n\nBullock opposes right-to-work legislation,<ref name=\"billingsgazette.com\">{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Charles S. |title=Bullock seeks governor\u2019s office vowing to create jobs, protect union rights |url=https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-seeks-governor-s-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect/article_7656c3e3-9820-587c-accf-f2e282daf128.html |website=Billings Gazette |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904225714/https://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/bullock-seeks-governor-s-office-vowing-to-create-jobs-protect/article_7656c3e3-9820-587c-accf-f2e282daf128.html |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> which allows workers to forgo paying union dues while still benefitting from union-negotiated labor contracts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Elizabeth G. |title=What right-to-work laws really mean |url=http://fortune.com/2012/01/31/what-right-to-work-laws-really-mean/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192005/http://fortune.com/2012/01/31/what-right-to-work-laws-really-mean/ |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Montana is the only state in the Upper Rocky Mountain region of the U.S. that does not have right-to-work legislation in place, and all of its neighboring states do not provide the same level of protection for labor unions.<ref name=\"billingsgazette.com\"/>\n\nOn January 18, 2018, Bullock filed an amicus brief to the U.S. Supreme Court in support of allowing labor unions to make \"agency fees\" mandatory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennison |first1=Mike |title=Gov. Bullock tells U.S. Supreme Court to preserve labor union `agency fees\u2019 |url=http://www.krtv.com/story/37305577/gov-bullock-tells-us-supreme-court-to-preserve-labor-union-agency-fees |website=KRTV.com |publisher=Cordillera Communications |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904193718/http://www.krtv.com/story/37305577/gov-bullock-tells-us-supreme-court-to-preserve-labor-union-agency-fees |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Bullock opposed the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Janus v. AFSCME]]'', and said in a statement: \"The US Supreme Court just overturned 40 years of settled law that workers, employers and unions across the country rely on. All the more ironic, the 5-4 decision cited ''Citizens United'' as a reason to do so.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MT officials react to Supreme Court organized labor ruling |url=https://nbcmontana.com/news/local/mt-officials-react-to-supreme-court-organized-labor-ruling |website=NBC Montana |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904192118/https://nbcmontana.com/news/local/mt-officials-react-to-supreme-court-organized-labor-ruling |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Steve Bullock}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Dark Money (film)|Dark Money]]'' (film)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://governor.mt.gov/ Governor Steve Bullock's official Montana government website]\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Montana/Government/Executive/Governor_Steve_Bullock|Steve Bullock}}\n* {{C-SPAN|stevebullock02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike McGrath]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Montana Department of Justice|Attorney General of Montana]]|years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tim Fox (politician)|Tim Fox]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Schweitzer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democra